Text: For the next four years, I want to grow as an individual.  I want to become a professional.  I have been around the dental field for the past few years, working in a dental office as a dental assistant.  I want to transition from being a dental assistant to a dentist.  I hope once I finish my four years at NYU I will be a confident and ethical doctor.  I find it so important to establish trusting relationship with patients, and the first thing is to do everything in the best interest of the patient.

Becoming a professional I believe takes time.  You need to be exposed to situations where you need to interact with other professionals and learn from them.  I believe you never stop learning to become a professional, it is a lifelong process.

As a health care professional, it is my duty to be ethical in all my actions and interactions. In treating patients, I will learn about the community around me so that I can be culturally sensitive and empathetic. I will also stick to a code of ethics that I will hold myself to. These will include putting my patient's desires, and health and oral health above my own personal desires. I will always provide my patients with all their options so that they may be able to make the best decision for their oral health based on their limitations and their understanding. I will always document my procedures and any important events that occur during my patient's visit, so that I can legally protect myself and themselves, and so that the work is documented for future review.

As a dental student, I will strive to learn about various oral health diseases and their symptoms, as well as different methods to improve oral hygiene. I will also learn the processes behind these diseases, and how to treat them. In the clinic, I will learn about the characteristics of each teeth, how to restore them via crowns, fillings, or root canals, how to remove caries, and how to create models and impressions for studying a patient's mouth or for preparing crowns or retainers. I will also learn how to interact with patients in terms of explaining procedures to them in words they can understand, in a manner that is respectful, and in a empathetic and ethical way (putting the patient's health and wants above my own personal desires). Finally, I hope to learn from my colleagues and practice communicating and working together with them.

Personally, as a professional I hope that I can possibly specialize in an area such as orthodontics, pediatrics, periodontics, or endodontics. However I will not limit myself to these specialties and I will explore other areas of specialty. I will also be satisfied with being a general dentist as well. Ultimately though, it depends on what I find I enjoy the most. I would also like to open my own clinic or at least have a clinic with another associate, especially because of the ease of accessibility to another dentist's opinion. Finally, I will strive to treat all my patients with respect, and all my colleagues with gratification and respect.

In becoming a health professional, I hope to provide my patients with the best care I can possibly give. That includes continuing my education by going to conventions and conferences to learn about the most up to date technologies for oral hygiene. I will also constantly challenge myself to better my work, by self-assessing myself often and checking on past work to see if anything should be redone. As a professional, I will strive for clear and concise communication with the patient and with my colleagues. I will also attempt to ensure that all my patients understand the importance of oral hygiene to overall health and the various ways they can take care of their teeth and health.

In my journey towards being a professional, I have learned how to interact with my peers and collaborate on work together. I have also learned how to study and help others when it comes to didactic and clinical work. I have recognized the importance of clear communication with peers to ensure understanding. I have also learned the importance of keeping the patient informed about their treatment. As I continue, I will learn how to speak to my patients in a professional and respectable manner. I will also learn how to communicate with my colleagues in a respectable and professional manner, especially over disagreements.

As a dental student, I will strive to learn how to best serve my patients, the community around me, and various communities around the country and the world. Specifically, I will become knowledgeable on the causes and symptoms of dental diseases as well as full body diseases, especially those that can become evident in the oral cavity. I will learn to treat patients both in the short-term and long-term capacity. I will also strive to treat all my patients with respect, sympathy, and ethically. I will always put the patient's health and desires above any personal gain, and I will be sure to refer my patient's to other doctors or dentists if I do not feel able to complete a procedure.

I think that ethical problems are the most important aspect in practicing dentistry. Throughout my studies at NYUCD, I will never allow myself to cheat, help in cheating or condoning such behaviors, because I think that it is detrimental to the society and the profession.

I would like to pass most, if not all, exams without failing. I will manage my time well so that I will have a plenty of time to rest on weekends. I want to enjoy NYC and plan to have some life by swimming and attending church on weekends, and traveling and meeting old and new friends on vacation.

First of all, I will absorb necessary knowledge in order to pass my classes and the board exams so that I know what I will be doing in the clinics. In clinic, I will learn from my GPD and instructors about how to behave as a dentist and uphold professional standards.

I think that becoming a professional is my life-long goal. Maintaining high ethical and moral standards has been one of the most important philosophical aspects of my life. Becoming a dental professional will allow me to apply my philosophy to be able to help treat patients and contribute to society. I will ask as many questions as possible that I have throughout my educational career at NYUCD to professors and peers, and utilize the school resources for progress in my dental career.

The orientation was long, but it already taught me many things about dental school. Interacting with orientation leaders allowed me to get a sense of how much studying will be done in the first two years. Also, the school made it clear how to use the resources and what the administrators and professors expect from me. I look forward to starting my classes tomorrow.

I would like to successfully complete my DDS program in 4 years without remediation and move onto a GPR residency in the NYC region. My goal is to make professional and personal contacts within NYUCD and in NYC. I would like to spend time studying the basic sciences and thoroughly learn general dentistry skills in the clinic, at the same time enjoying the materials. In doing so, I intend to get involved in many outreach trips and school-related clubs, in particular the Korean Student organization and ADEA. I would like to become close friends with people from my group and other classmates whom I will get to meet. In my D3 and D4 years, I am interested in participating elective and Honors programs because even if I become a GP, I want to be knowledgeable about systemic oral disease detections. I would like to be a helpful member of the NYUCD community and reach our professional goals as a whole.

Dentistry is one of the few professions that requires not only the high practical prowess but also moral and ethical standards. There are several factors that make a dentist a good professional but I believe one of the most important things for a professional is to be independent and proficient in their job. In other words, professionals should be consistent and punctual. In addition, it is important to follow the rules and regulation to prevent reckless and nefarious malpractices. However, this does not mean that one should be stagnant and passive in their profession. Rather, I believe it is important for professional to actively seek out for improvements and advancements. This can be achieved through working, discussing and researching issues with different professionals in various different fields in the profession. Moreover, it is important for professionals to have appropriate moral and ethical standards. I believe these are some of the factors that are crucial in becoming a good professional.

Ever since I realized that dentistry is one of the few professions that seamlessly blend both artistry and science, I was fascinated by it. It is, thus natural, that I have vast interest in becoming an orthodontist. However, I would like to be exposed to a various different dental specialties not only through school curriculum but also through community outreach and volunteer service. As a dental student, I would like to graduate dental school in good standing with proficiency in general dentistry. As a health care professional, I would like to learn not only the technical skills but also the interpersonal skills to have fulfilling relationships with various different patients. I realize this skill would require me to uphold my ethical principles as well as the rules and regulation at all times. Moreover, I hope that I would be more open-minded and bold in making decisions. In addition, I would like to have a good lifelong relationship with my peers in both private and professional environment.

I want to always be putting my patients first above all us when I progress through dental school and eventually in my professional career. I believe that as a healthcare professional, we have a duty to provide our patients with the most effective treatment and when we know we are not the right person for our patient to not hesitate and relay our patient to the right person. 

While in dental school I want to always put forth an honest effort in my work and not take any shortcuts because I want to make sure I really understand what is being taught as my future patients deserve that kind of honest effort from their dentist. Also I want to contribute to an honest learning environment and reach out to any peers that I may see struggling.

I hope to work not just hard but smart and produce the results necessary to have multiple options ready when I graduate. Currently I am really interested in the field of pediatrics so I want to put myself in the position to learn as much as I can about the field and make sure when I do make a decision that it is an informed one.

Aside from the points mentioned in the public self reflection portion, I want to become more open minded and be better at taking criticism as that will be important when dealing with patients as well as my future dental team. So far into the year I have been good about being punctual but I want to persist in having good punctuality as it was a weakness of mine in the past.

I believe in order to become a professional in the field of dentistry, you must go beyond knowing just the craft of dentistry. It also means how you present yourself and how you treat the people you are working with. For instance punctuality and respect are two important aspects that patients look for in a dentist aside from his/her technical abilities. A dentist that is unorganized or difficult to make appointments with is hard for the patient to trust in putting their oral health in. Also even though the dentist is the head of his/her practice, it takes a cohesive and supportive team of individuals to treat the dental patient properly. Thus, a dentist that does not present him/herself to the dental team in a professional manner will never gain their trust.

At this point I am not entirely certain where I want to practice dentistry. I do know that if I feel that I am not ready once I graduate from dental school I will immediately look to do some residency to get myself to the level of competency I am comfortable to practice solo. I do want to eventually have my own dental practice and after some time try to expand.

I hope to become competent enough that when I graduate my friends will fully trust me to perform dentistry on them if need be. I hope to at least maintain the passion I had for this field when I walked to my first class this year and hopefully expand that passion when I graduate. I want to work  hard and to always be humble of the fact that I should never be satisfied with my level of competence in dentistry. As long as I keep learning I know I will be more competent than yesterday but not as competent as I can be tomorrow. Areas that I need to work on is to be less stubborn and more open minded, and I need to be organized with my clinics and lab from the get go to not get messy habits.

I have always considered myself a very ethical person.  I strive to live my life a certain way, and to treat others as I would want to be treated.  My family dentist is a man who I feel is a very ethical person, who always does the right thing and puts the needs of his patients first.  While I have heard stories about other dentists refusing to see a certain type of patient, my family dentist always has an open door.  He believes that his job wasnt to make as much money as possible, but to service others and give back to his community.  As a future dentist this is how I want to run my practice.  I want to be known as the dentist who will see everyone, no matter what his or her situation may be.  I feel that to be a great dentist, you have to be a great person first and foremost.  You have to admit and correct your mistakes.  Above all, you have to truly care about your work and your patients.  You have to WANT to make a difference in someones life.

My private statement is basically the same as my public statement.  I see how the dentists that I know live their lives, and I want that lifestyle.  I have never been the one to seek appraisal, but I want to be known as a great dentist, someone who listens to and actually cares about his patients.  I have no idea where I would like to practice, but I am leaning more towards going back home to Niagara-on-the-Lake.  I do however feel guilty about pursuing a career in dentistry, as my family back home owns a couple of vineyards, and there is always lots of work to do.  However, now my dad has to bear the brunt of the work by himself.  While I do know that he is proud of what Ive accomplished, I would like to go back home when I graduate and help my parents out as much, if not more, than they have helped me.  I am leaning towards working 3-4 days a week at my practice, and possible 2-3 days helping out on the farm.  I feel like that would be the ideal situation.
There is nothing that I would want to add in my private self-reflection that would be different from my public reflection.

I believe that a professional should possess the knowledge, skills, personality and morals to make her/him successful.  I have always wanted to become a dentist and work in the health-care profession because I truly like helping people; especially making people smile and happy.  However, I have noticed that a lot of people I know would say to me,  you are going to make so much money,  but to be honest I do not care about money.  To me, dentistry would be the perfect lifestyle and not a job/work.  How can it be work if you get to do what you love and are interested in everyday?  I get to interact with my patients and be there for them, whether it be dental related or otherwise.  I want to be known as the "people's dentist", where everyone knows my name and knows that my door is open to everyone. While I know that I am a long ways away from becoming a dentist, I am enjoying the adventure, and counting down the days that I can finally be called a dentist.

Being only 3 weeks into dental school I have not had much professional progress to date.  However, I feel that with the start of the pre-clinical labs that I am very slowly becoming a dentist.  Some of our classes have made me realize how we should be interacting with not only our future patients, but with one another and our colleagues.

To me, teeth are much more than just small, calcified structures whose main purpose are the mechanical breakdown of food.  While they can cause considerable pain and discomfort, teeth can also bring joy and happiness.  I have always believed that dentists treat much more than just patients teeth.  A dentist has the capability to improve a persons life through their smile.  A dentist can improve how a person views themselves and possibly how others view them.  My desire has always been to become a dentist so that I can make a difference in my patients lives, no matter how big or small.  As a future health care professional, I believe that everyone should be entitled to dental care.  I am looking forward to giving back to communities, both locally and abroad, through the various outreach programs that NYUCD offers.  However, to be able to successfully and efficiently provide dental care, I must first gain the knowledge and skills that are required to provide patients with the best possible treatment.  I am excited to start this journey, and am anxious for the day when I can help change someones life.

Throughout these next four years, I look forward to being molded into a competent and professional healthcare provider. I hope to build new professional relationships with my fellow colleagues and faculty. My time at NYUCD is an opportunity to best prepare myself for the demands of this field and the needs of my patients.

Throughout these next four years, I look forward to being molded into a competent and professional healthcare provider. I hope to build new professional relationships with my fellow colleagues and faculty. My time at NYUCD is an opportunity to best prepare myself for the demands of this field and the needs of my patients.

In my public statement I said I want to fix people's faces. I know that sounds kind of vague, and I haven't found a better way to express that just yet, but what I mean is to fix whatever facial deformities or defects that are present. My pre-dental society in undergrad would have dental health professionals speak every week and I remember one in particular where he should photos of people that had to wear facial prosthetics to cover what were essentially parts of their face or jaw missing. At the time I thought the very fact a prosthodontist could make something and give it to the patient to wear was amazing. But what I really want to do is go one step beyond that and make wearing the prosthetic unnecessary. Facial reconstruction is I think the coolest thing. From what I know I think leans heavily toward OMS and bigger hospital surgeries which I rather prefer than private practice. When we talk about improving quality of life, I believe there is no greater way to increase that than down this path.

In undergrad, I was a Human Biology major, but I also minored in Philosophy. One particular article sticks out in my mind whenever I think of professionalism and what it means. The article talked about "civic professionalism" and how there is an inherent contract, or trust, between the public and the professional. And moreover, we as professionals should give back to the community for without the community providing patients how would we have learned our craft. I think that as I progress throughout dental school this will become more relevant and I know whatever opportunity I have to give back or do a community outreach I will try my best to make it happen. What's the point of having these skills if we don't try to use them to promote the greatest degree of quality life we can.

My journey to dental school has left me with a number of experiences that have shaped not only the type of dentist I want to be, but also how I view the relationship between one's oral health and their quality of life. I've worked with dental professionals from around the United States, Mexico, and Australia and have a strong sense of what I want to get out of dentistry -- I simply want to be able to fix people's faces. To me,  a person's face is their most important feature giving them the self-confidence to go out and interact with the world. Now what path this aim of mine takes me down from here on out I don't know, but what I do know is that throughout all the pitfalls I've overcome I will not lose sight of my goal. I feel privileged to be apart of this great profession.

Dentistry is a creative and independent field. It is a very flexible profession that allows me to pursue other dental related interests outside of working in a group or office. Some of my future goals in dentistry include volunteering for programs that help underserved communities in the U.S and poverty-stricken areas throughout the world where dental care is not readily available. New York University College of Dentistry is in one of the best schools to facilitate my goals because it has many programs that serve the underserved communities. Furthermore, NYUCD has a diverse patient population, which allows me to interact with people of all different socioeconomic backgrounds. As a dentist, I wish gradually become a cherished counselor and confidant. I realized the personal contact integrated within dentistry permits a unique interaction with people of diverse ages, cultures, and backgrounds.

I know that there isn't much room to procrastinate in dental school, so I am going to try to study and go over the notes every day this semester. I've heard that pulling all-nighters is not a good idea, so I should remind myself not to become lazy. I want to develop a regular sleeping pattern so that I can go to classes and use my time wisely when I am awake. I am a little stressed about what I am going to face over the next four years, but I feel more responsibility in what I learn and do now. I think it's good to have a little bit of stress as I study and participate in labs, but I will try not to be too overwhelmed.

I chose to become a dentist even before I started my undergrad, and I am very happy to be here. I am finally at a stage where I get to learn the "practical" knowledge here at NYUCD, and I feel more responsible for understanding and applying the knowledge. All the information I receive in lectures and labs will be essential for my future practice, and I just want to keep up with the workload. I am interested in going into pediatric dentistry, so I will have to try really hard to get where I want to be. I love how our school has a very diverse student body, and I hope I can make a lot of friends. I am pretty excited to start a new phase in my life, and I just want to make the most out of it.

To become ethical, one must first be able to know what is right and what is wrong.  And then, after know what is right and what is wrong, one must understand the appropriate actions following the determination.  It takes knowledge, experience, and courage to become truly ethical, and I aspire to become a great dentist that could deliver this to my future patients.

When I was young, I was scared of going to dentists because I am fearful. As I grow up, I learn more and more about this world to understand that danger is real, but fear is just an illusion that we create spontaneously to help ourselves overcome the obstacles.  I am very interested in the fear aspect of dentistry, and I would love to spend the next four years in NYUCD not only studying dentistry and perfecting my clinical skills, but also learn how to properly manage others' as well as my fear.

Becoming a professional is a challenging task, but it certainly is a requirement for dentistry.  As dentists, we are responsible for other people's health and in order to carry the required task successfully, professionalism must be incorporated into every dentist's life.  As many Doctors in NYUCD mentioned, we don't want patients to see us wearing shirts, because it just doesn't portray to them that we have the capabilities, as professionals, to be capable of treating them.

Being a health care professional is somewhat like being a tooth in the mouth.  After doing my wax up today, I have a deeper understanding of the precision and accuracy required to wax up a tooth, because if it doesn't fit perfectly, it is just not good enough to be part of the system( i.e. joining rest of the teeth to perform its functions).  Being a professional not only means one has to be good at performing the required task (i.e. teeth for mastication), but also means to look like a professional (i.e. the esthetic of teeth)
Since it has only been the first two weeks, I have sort of started understanding more and more and the scientific and clinical background of the knowledge required to become a competent dentist.

I still remember in my personal statement for dental school application, I wrote a story about how a little boy was frightened to go to the dentists.  But 15 years later, this little boy is a grown man and started learning all the knowledge that is required to become a competent dentist.  I wish that after four years of school, I can step out of NYUCD being confident to treat patients, and to grow up to become a respected and compassionate dentist like my parents, whom I admire and aspire to.

Ethical values are unique to dental professionals because dentists have a "special" role in the communities they participate in.  Dentists form a trusting relationship which their patients and with their community and therefore have a powerful position both socially and ethically.  This empowered position may serve as a struggling point for many professionals because it gives them a sense of entitlement and  limitless boundaries.  I think it is most important for dental professionals to remember what motivated them to enter the field in the first place:  promoting preventative oral healthcare as well as treating oral issues all the while staying within ethical boundaries to ensure the optimal health of their patients.

During my junior year of college I had the opportunity to go on a medical brigade to Honduras where I worked with doctors, dentists, and oral surgeons.  Before the brigade, I had wanted to be an orthopedist, but after my experiences in Honduras, I knew that I wanted to be a dentist.  Through my pre-med major and my sculpture minor, I have attained the skills necessary to succeed and excel in dental school.

Within the next four years, I want to feel confident enough in my clinical and diagnostic abilities that I will be able to accurately assess and treat a wide variety of patients.  I want to develop a language between myself and my patients that is both educational and understandable and help to make my patients feel a part of their treatment plan.  I want to be prepared to diagnose and treat a wide variety of patients with a wide variety of dental and oral issues when I exit NYUCD in four years.  I want to have the ability to give my patients a number of treatment options and make them feel integrated in their treatment plan.  I expect that I will continuously learn and expose myself to the dynamic and ever-changing oral health care system and that my diagnosis and treatments will reflect those changes throughout my career.

Within the next four years, I want to feel confident enough in my clinical and diagnostic abilities that I will be able to accurately assess and treat a wide variety of patients.  I want to develop a language between myself and my patients that is both educational and understandable and help to make my patients feel a part of their treatment plan.  I want to be prepared to diagnose and treat a wide variety of patients with a wide variety of dental and oral issues when I exit NYUCD in four years.  I want to have the ability to give my patients a number of treatment options and make them feel integrated in their treatment plan.  I expect that I will continuously learn and expose myself to the dynamic and ever-changing oral health care system and that my diagnosis and treatments will reflect those changes throughout my career.

I've worked my entire life to prepare myself to become a respected healthcare professional. I studied hard in elementary school so I could get into gate classed in Junior High, and I excelled in Junior High to ensure that I could take AP classes in High School.  I graduated in the top 1% of my high school so I could study at an excellent college.  I graduated from USC with honors to make sure I could study at one of the top dental schools in the United States.  Now, at NYUCD, I have all the tools necessary to become a respected oral health care professional.

During my junior year of college I had the opportunity to go on a medical brigade to Honduras where I worked with doctors, dentists, and oral surgeons.  Before the brigade, I had wanted to be an orthopedist, but after my experiences in Honduras, I knew that I wanted to be a dentist.  Through my pre-med major and my sculpture minor, I have attained the skills necessary to succeed and excel in dental school.

Ethics plays a key role in the profession of dentistry especially because you are working as a team and have patients you are responsible for. It is important to learn through experience and classes about what it really takes to be ethical in all areas of this profession.

My goal for these next 4 years and beyond is to become a competent dentist, but also a person who is extremely professional and approachable. I want to master all the skills it takes to complete dental school and become a dentist who is confident and efficient. I want to use the knowledge and skills I learn here to further my career in either orthodontics or endodontics. I want to work as hard as I can in hopes to become a very competent professional because my patients are going to count on me. I want to be able to be extremely professional and learn how to do all of this and have a successful practice.
I believe I can be professional but I also think that I have a lot to learn about little details that would make me even more competent and professional.

I think that becoming a professional takes time because there is a lot that goes into it. We all know how to be professional in some way or another, but it takes more than just learning the craft of the profession. To become a professional we need to have the skills and ethical values that is necessary when being a healthcare provider. Through the experiences of dental school I hope to gain more knowledge that will make me a a better professional.
Right now I feel that I can act in a professional manner in school and when working with others.

A dentist, in my opinion, is someone who will use their knowledge, skills, and own moral codes to provide the best care for their patients. My goal for these next 4 years and beyond is to not only become a competent dentist, but also a person who is extremely professional and approachable. I want to master all the skills it takes to complete dental school and become a dentist who is confident and efficient. I want to use the knowledge and skills I learn here to further my career in either orthodontics or endodontics.
I will make decisions that I can sleep easy about. I will behave in a way that my conscience is always clear. I will conduct myself in a manner such that my grandmother would be proud.

In addition to attaining (at least) proficiency in a variety of proceeders, I hope to:
Establish 1:1 relationships with faculty
Form lasting friendships with classmates
Become a perpetual student, even beyond dental school
Develop a sense of self awareness 
Learn to deal effectively with stress 
Learn efficient time management skills

I hope to develop my interest in academic dentistry by becoming a teaching assistant. 
I hope to develop my interest in research by maintaining my involvement in research through the honors in research track and the available summer research programs. 
I hope to continue my life long love of service on an outreach trip, either locally or abroad. 
I will objectively discover the many specialties of dentistry.

More is expected of me as I become a professional- from my family, friends, and the community. It is a big responsibility, one that will put me in a role model like position. I am looking forward to moving into professional life and all that comes with it, and I know that the personal growth that will occur in the next few years will put me on the path to becoming the professional that can make all the aforementioned (and myself!) proud.

Being a professional is more than being proficient or even advanced in a specific set of skills. Much is expected of a professional from family, friends, the community, and of course our patients. We are to behave ethically and responsibly with integrity and emotional intelligence.

In the few short weeks we've been here at NYUCD, I can feel as though I have truly begun my journey toward becoming a professional. I am learning the qualities of a professional and a professional's role in the community, as well as the beginnings of hands on dentistry.

I hope to integrate my interests in research and teaching not only into my education but also into my career, finding a balance between practice and academics. I will share my strengths with others and acknowledge and seek help for my weaknesses. I will leave dental school with a network of colleagues and close friends. I will seize every opportunity for community involvement both locally and abroad. I will maintain a positive attitude always!

Patient care should always be the practitioners number one priority. Financial gain should never be the driving force for the practitioners services. Being competent in ones field, also means knowing when to seek help from other practitioners.

A professional is an individual who practices their profession not only in the workplace but their profession is their way of life. They follow a set role of ethics and will oblige by it for the betterment of the community.

I hope to acquire the knowledge to become a dental practitioner, but to also gain the skill set which will allow me to become more competent as a professional. Furthermore, I would like to grow as an ethical individual and be able to provide care to the community by using my acquired knowledge in the dental field.

I truly believe that my work ethic and determination to do well over the next four years will allow me to become a successful dentist. I am extremely interested in orthodontistry and hope to build the connections I need to be able to eventually specialize.

Becoming a professional is an important part of being a dentist. It gives patients the confidence to put their health care in your hands and allows for strong patient-doctor relationships to form.  I hope to become a competent professional and build a strong network with other professionals in the health care field to optimize the treatment of my patients.

For me, a person's smile is one of the most important features of the body. It is a way to express happiness, show kindness, and has to ability to improve your own or even someone else's mood. I believe that being a dentist and giving someone the confidence of a great smile is a highly rewarding and satisfying job that I hope to become competent in over the next four years. This not only includes completing the course work, but also pushing myself to study and learn outside the boundaries of the curriculum to become a health care professional that is able to cooperate and coordinate with others. I hope to become a dentist with an influence that is larger than the confines of the office, and is highly involved in local and regional outreach programs.

I am still trying to figure out exactly what I would like to do when I become a dentist. I have thought about pediatric dentistry for a while since I have spent so much time working with kids, but I think that solely working with kids might be difficult; especially if the parents are trying to be protective when they see that their child is possibly in pain. I have also thought about oral surgery, but I'm not so sure that I want to be in school for an addition six years after dental school. Now I am currently thinking about going into orthodontics or periodontics, because I can't see myself being satisfied with being a general dentist. I have also thought about going into academia and teaching at a dental school when I graduate; however as of now I think I would like to practice. Over the next few years I hope to figure out exactly what I would like to do as a career after dental school.

I think that in order to be a professional, one must be respected by the people they come in contact with. If this is at the work place, they should be knowledgeable about their job and treat everyone with respect. To be a professional, one should be responsible and have a sense of urgency when it comes to having deadlines. They should always be setting goals for themselves to either achieve or surpass. I believe that it can take work in becoming a professional, but everyone can reach that goal. In regards to myself as a professional, that will have to be something that I will have to work on when I become a dentist. I treat people with respect and I take responsibility for my actions. Over the next few years I will become more knowledgeable about the profession which will help me become a professional.

I think that in order to be a professional, one must be respected by the people they come in contact with. If this is at the work place, they should be knowledgeable about their job and treat everyone with respect. To be a professional, one should be responsible and have a sense of urgency when it comes to having deadlines. They should always be setting goals for themselves to either achieve or surpass. I believe that it can take work in becoming a professional, but everyone can reach that goal. In regards to myself as a professional, that will have to be something that I will have to work on when I become a dentist. I treat people with respect and I take responsibility for my actions. Over the next few years I will become more knowledgeable about the profession which will help me become a professional.

When I originally decided that I wanted to become a dentist, I thought I wanted to either become a pediatric dentist or an oral surgeon. When I went for my Master's Degree in Biomolecular Sciences, I began to think about the academic side of dentistry as a profession. I enjoyed doing research and learning about how certain signaling pathways can affect teeth development; I investigating the role of Hedgehog signaling in regulating proliferation in the development of teeth in zebrafish. The research that I might want to do after dental school if I end up becoming a professor would be on oral cancer treatments. I am mostly leaning towards practicing dentistry as a profession, but I want to keep my options open in regards to a career in academia. I hope to learn more about the specialties over the next few years and seeing what I would like best as a potential career.

Over the next four years, I want to focus on becoming an excellent health care provider. I plan on doing so by not only practicing my skills in pre-clinic and clinic, but also by learning how to establish a trusting relationship with my patients. I want to work hard to be a great dentist, but one who exemplifies passion and true dedication to their career. Ultimately, my goal is to specialize in Pediatric dentistry, focusing on children with special needs. I realized my passion while working with a pediatric dentist who saw many children with Autism, Down syndrome, and severe ADHD (amongst other special needs cases). I knew that there would be no feeling more rewarding than helping these kids, many of whom do not have access to dental care. I am incredibly passionate about what I want to do with my career and as a result, I plan on staying active in the Pedo and Special Needs organizations and getting involved in pediatric outreach at NYUCD.

Working as a health care professional comes with many expectations, especially from the patients. They expect you to not only diagnose a particular issue, but treat it as well. They need you to understand their oral health, and explain it to them so they are informed. They trust your decisions in treatment options, and want a proper referral if need be. As a future dentist, I realize how high the bar is raised, and how much of a conscious effort I need to make to ensure that I am meeting my patients expectations. I want to understand and appreciate how each case is different, so that I can cater what I know to the specific needs of my future patients.

A tooth problem is not simply a health problem; it also affects patients confidence, self-esteem and the facial expressions that reflect our inner feelings. My desire to make a difference and transform someones life has sparked my motivation to pursue a career in dentistry. Access to dental care is a pressing issue and it is my duty to give back to the community though NYUCD outreach programs. There is no greater feeling than continuing to give back to those in need. Giving back to the community as a Dentist requires foundational knowledge, clinical skills, morals and integrity converting me to a professional who considers education not just an investment for the future but a lifestyle. I truly believe that the service of a dentist rises above restoring smiles and reaches up to restoring lives.

Aside from the practice and technical aspects of dentistry, through working with various dentists, I have learned firsthand the need for personal integrity and hard work as well as the importance of motivation and empathy in improving patients' dental health. It is important to be a dentist whom patients can trust and be able to relieve their anxiety and pain.

Going through 3.5 years of teeth realignment was a valuable experience. And as eager as I was, I always had a lot of questions for my orthodontist and began to develop the dream of how fascinating it would be to be on other side and integrate art, science and handcraft to help people with their teeth. To realize my dream, I did my major in biological sciences and used every opportunity to improve my manual dexterity. During my college years, I volunteered as a dental assistant. Aside from the practice and technical aspects of dentistry, through working with various dentists, I have learned firsthand the need for personal integrity and hard work as well as the importance of motivation and empathy in improving patients' dental health. I am also glad that I have been able to gain experience in research. I have published two scientific articles in my school's scientific journal and have had the honor of working in Dr. Robert Siliciano's research lab at Johns Hopkins University. Most recently, I was enrolled in the MSc Program in biotechnology at Johns Hopkins and have completed courses with an A+ GPA.

I very much look forward to the honor of being a member of a great community devoted to understanding and fighting dental maladies. Through the years, I have strived through my studies, dental experiences, manual projects and research to realize my dream and dedicate myself to lifelong learning, caring, teaching, and discovering in the field of Dentistry.

There are numerous intriguing factors that interested me in the field of dentistry. This includes the balance of scientific knowledge, decision making, and the precise execution of each case with each patient. However, there are two things that captivated me the most, with the first being that it enforces the importance of  thinking outside of the box , and being able to envision a new appearance for each patient. This was evident when the treatment options presented to patients and the way each case were handled were different based on the medical history, age and current oral condition of the patients. Secondly, the importance of using perceptual and hands on ability to fulfill that treatment plan. Pursuing a career in dentistry will give me the opportunity to use my knowledge and talent in a field that leaves me feeling accomplished.

I will plan to learn the principles of professional conduct as a dental professional during my time as a student at NYU college of dentistry. I will learn how to analyze, provide dental care and make decisions in a patient centered manner. I will learn the principles of patient confidentiality and conduct myself in a manner fitting a professional.

During my time as a dental student at New York University I hope to obtain the knowledge needed to successfully treat a community. Proper treatment of a community not only entails excellent dental work but also as a healthcare professional involved in health promotion, community outreach, and a team member of a inter professional health care team. I will hope to accomplish these goals and be competent in these tasks by obtaining knowledge not only from classes, but from faculty, peers, mentors, and patients. I plan to take advantage of the diverse environment NYU provides which will help me grow as both a professional and an individual.

A professional is someone that is trusted and looked up to by the public because a professional possesses a subset of specialized skills that is used to serve the public. Transforming from an undergraduate student, to a dental student, to a professional will require obtaining not only specialized knowledge of dental techniques/ treatments but also an understanding of the individual and the community. The professional must be able to act in a patient centered manner in which the patient is able to access the best treatment possible for their specific case. To become a professional I must understand how to obtain multiple solutions which benefit the patient.

A professional is someone that has mastered his or her field and who is competent at handling all the curve balls that life can throw at him or her. A professional has to be held to the highest standards that the field and society dictates. By mastering the course work and the clinical skills here at NYCD I hope to make a big leap towards becoming a professional, but I believe that becoming a professional is a life long process that does not end with ones education.

I begin my time here at NYCD with the hope to become a competent and successful dentist, through my work to eventually help others while being a positive role model and lastly to grow as a person and lead a balance life. I am certain that the road towards achieving my goals will be difficult but I feel prepared for the challenges ahead. The next four year will fly by and hopefully I look back on my time here as great experience that formed me as person.

Becoming a professional is not only important to me but it is necessary in the health care setting. Integrity and autonomy are the two descriptive words that come to mind when I think of the word professional. In becoming a health care professional it is an absolute must for one to possess integrity. First, integrity provides the basis of truthfulness and consistency that patients and other healthcare professionals can learn to rely on. Next, every professional must have the ability to self-assess and govern ones own actions. This is where autonomy comes into play. A professional knows his limitations because he is independent, however, in knowing his limitations he simply knows as a professional he is able to ask for assistance through referring or consulting other health care providers. I will become a health care professional, although, the only way I will get there is through maintaining my integrity and learning to become autonomous within the field of dentistry.

I am here to become the absolute best health care provider that I can possibly become. That being said I will not settle for meeting the bench mark as I will be in constant competition with myself. I will do this by making sure that I surpass the median as I continuously strive to reach unprecedented heights. At this point in my education I am unable to commit to a specific specialty due to my inexperience at this time, however, I am determined to specialize. I have considered the oral maxillofacial route. I feel this would be an optimal career choice as I am never satisfied with the present state of my education. I am always looking to gain new insights and also having a passion for research and the more medical side of dentistry I believe OMS is my calling. Lastly, I would like to use my time here at NYU to build a solid networking foundation. It is a privilege to have been offered the opportunity to attend such a great school and I have full intentions on consuming as many resources as possible during my time here.
I hope to become a competent dental practitioner and hold myself to the highest ethical and moral standards. I hope to gain the skill set to provide dental care to the best of my abilities.

Regardless of whether I am going to be a healthcare professional or not, I expect the utmost integrity from myself.  I have a set standard of morals and beliefs based on my faith in Christ.  Although, I am nowhere near to being perfect, I understand what is the difference between what is right and wrong.  It is my personal choice to ensure that the right decision is made for the well-being of everyone around me.

A professional healthcare provider isn't just someone who provides the treatments, but someone who understands and exhibits the importance of building genuine relationships with their patients, community, and colleagues.  There is a wide range of reasons on why people choose to go into healthcare, but to me, I find my personal reason as my drive to become a competent provider.  I just love to serve others in any way possible, and my best skill set just happens to stem from my manual dexterity.  Serving even my peers brings me joy, so I will strive my best to seek as much wisdom, advice, and help to provide the best quality care.  I am a firm believer in caring for others with a giving heart.  There is no rewarding gain from trying to "give" with a heart of expecting something in return.  I have a long way before I become this professional that I expect myself to be, but I have faith, patience, and perseverance that it will happen little by little.

The journey to becoming a professional is a difficult one where times of hardship and questionable situations arise.  It is how I handle these moments that will build my character as a future professional and caretaker.  I believe that as long as I understand and surrender the idea that I cannot accomplish everything on my own strength and knowledge, I will become the well-rounded professional I seek to be.  I want to continue listening to the wisdom that others share, while discerning which ones are applicable to me.  There are non-negotiable standards that I follow and certain ideas that I strive to adhere to.  A few of them being honest, despite the consequences (dishonest consequences will be far more severe), logically unbiased yet compassionate, admitting wrong or unknowns yet voicing my opinions, etc.

Health related professionals are in high demand in the United States and not all people have access to quality healthcare. It is important to me to be able to provide quality care to a diverse patient population with a plethora of oral conditions. It is vital to see the human body as one organism, where different symptoms of various diseases manifest themselves throughout, and to be able to identify these symptoms to refer the patient for appropriate care. I am confident that at NYU I will be able to learn to not only treat dental conditions, but to understand various pathologies and how they affect oral health care. I expect the next four years to be challenging, but rewarding. I plan to do community outreach and go on one of the service trips. I look forward to using my hands in the lab, since I am very artistically oriented and this is one of the reasons I even entered dentistry in the first place. By graduation I hope to be a well adapted dentist who is able to provide quality care and establish a close relationship with my patients.

I expect to master the didactic material and develop as a comprehensive and respected professional. I want to service the community in a positive and formative way through outreach both domestically and overseas. I hope to matriculate into the workforce as a confident dentist who is able to make thoughtful and ethical decisions when working with colleagues and other healthcare professionals.

I hope to learn from my mistakes while I still have supervision and become the best dentist I can when I graduate.  I hope to have support when I'm stressed because I have a problem putting assignments off to the last minute and that needs to change both in my academic and professional life.

My ideal experience at NYUCD would be learning to be a complete dentist, with both the knowledge the field requires as well as well developed hand skills to perform every necessary procedure. My goal is to learn about several specialty options so I can have an open mind after my four years here in case I want to continue my education.  In addition, I hope to get to know all of my colleagues on a personal level, and to be able to rely on them for support, networking, and friendship as I complete school and move on to a successful career.

Over the next 4 years at NYUCD, I am certain not only will I gain the necessary skills and knowledge to pass all the competency requirements, I will be a respected dentist with great moral ethics and integrity. I wish to  excel and eventually master the technical skills required of the dental profession. Throughout my clinical rotation, I plan to endlessly improve my patient care and work on effective communication. I realize the importance of building a network, so I plan to reach out to peers and faculty to develop life long positive relationships that will not only benefit each party but also to the patients. I plan to utilize school and community resources and build leadership roles by participating in student groups or community projects. One of the priorities of dentist should be their responsibilities to the community, thus I plan to volunteer in both local and international outreach program to both enrich myself and to help others. Last, but not least, I wish to always maintain a positive working attitude and a thirst of knowledge that will aid me in my lifelong pursuit in this wonderful healthcare profession.

During my first semester in dental school, my fellow colleagues and I worked together in our professionalism and ethics in healthcare course to develop core values in which our class aspires to embody.  Some believe that our core values should be innate, however, I believe it was important to restate these values as many of us can easily neglect them.  It was important for us to work together because as aspiring dentists, these ethical values hold an important part of our foundation as a dentist.  Examples of our core values include acting with integrity and honesty, demonstrating professionalism, serving others, being patient-centered, embracing excellence, creating and fostering a collaborative learning environment, and valuing diversity.

Being a professional requires many characteristics, all of which I hope to develop through my experiences while I am in dental school.  I believe that two important cores are your knowledge in the basic sciences and your ethical and moral behavior.  The former is necessary because without a solidified background regarding these sciences, one may not be able to deliver proper oral healthcare.  The latter is necessary because as a professional dentist, you need to act with a certain set of ethics and morals that is expected of you.  Becoming a professional does not occur overnight; it is a step-by-step process.  My first step was completing my first semester at dental school, and I hope to expand on this foundation in order to become the professional I need to be.

After my first semester in dental school, I can see a dramatic increase in my professionalism.  Being exposed to the professional world of dentistry has allowed me to assimilate into the profession, as well as understand the characteristics that is required of me as a professional.  I have learned information in fundamental science courses that will allow me to build on this foundation of mine in order to best delivery proper oral healthcare.  Part of being a professional is understanding the complexity of information that is required; my first semester courses has allowed me to progress in this manner.

As a current dental student, I look forward to becoming professionally competent in an important field of healthcare.  A strong background in sciences regarding dentistry is a key fundamental that must be established as a foundation for every student.  As an individual, I strive towards delivering efficient oral healthcare to patients.  There are patients that are unable to access the proper dental treatment that they require, so I believe that it is important, as well as necessary as future dentists, to provide this treatment.   Another key aspect of the dental profession is building positive relationships with patients; this relationship can help alleviate any barriers that may exist within the dentist-patient relationship and develop better communication skills.  In the bigger picture, being a dentist isn't about succeeding on your own, but excelling as a group and as a community.

My individual goals include improving myself academically, professionally, and socially. In regards to my academics, I would like to be competent and proficient in the scientific knowledge that I will eventually need to use and to excel in all my classes. I would also like to master the manual dexterity and patient care that is required of dentistry. Outside of academics, I would aim to establish a balance between schoolwork and my social life and to be as happy and as mentally sound as possible. Professionally, I want to build long-lasting meaningful relationships with my classmates as well as faculty members.

I hope to exude more confidence to become a responsible and professionally competent dentist once I leave NYUCD. I believe that mannerism and appearance is important in how the public views not only NYUCD but the dental profession as a whole.  I hope to also carry on the NYUCD mission goal of community service even when I graduate and give back to the community.

I view professionalism as a necessary tool that will allow me to provide the best dental care to my patients, keep them satisfied, and happy to see me. For me being professional means being competent in all aspects of dental care, and know where my patients can get medical care beyond what dentistry can offer. I believe that technical proficiency is very important in dental profession (mostly patients will expect me to “fix” their teeth), but being solely a perfect teeth technician will not make me a great dental professional. I believe that on top of great technical skills, a successful dental professional must also exhibit excellent communication skills, deep medical knowledge, and concentrate on improving patients’ quality of life through prevention of diseases.

My goal in NYUCD is to build a strong foundation for my future career in dentistry. This implies pursuit of academic excellence, constant drive to gain hands-on medical experience, development of good values and a humane approach to treating patients.
I intend to gain knowledge and confidence that are required for this purpose. I believe that in this fast and dynamically developing profession I will never stop learning. For this reason, I also intend to develop the necessary skills that will allow me to work in a team, and collaborate with other healthcare providers to ensure that the patient's interests and needs are served in the best way possible.

To learn how to maintain a standard of excellence amongst the dental community that translates into leadership amidst the progression of dentistry.

To master my role in the patient-doctor relationship, for the efficient benefit of my growth as a healthcare provider and the improvement of overall patient health.

To fully understand all specialties of dentistry and the compliment between them to a degree that allows me to make an educated, prepared, and appropriate decision on which aspect of dentistry is suited best for me.

To identify deficiencies amongst communities worldwide and how to meet those need effectively.

common goals:
      - As a group we are excited to gain the skills and knowledge necessary to become a competent dental professional. We believe it is very important to understand a patient's needs extend beyond the mouth. It is vital to have a holistic approach to treating a patient and be respectful of an individual's culture and beliefs.
      
      individual goals:
      -While at NYU I am to keep an open mind and talk to as many peers and faculty members as possible. I plan on participating in outreach opportunities domestically and abroad. I hope to incorporate my experiences and education in public health when I graduate from NYU College of Dentistry to have a career in both clinical work and research.For me, it is important to increase access to dental services in my community and emphasize education as a means of prevention.

Becoming a professional is something that will occur as we gain more experiences interacting with faculty, peers, and patients. Our coursework, in ethics for example, challenges us to think about what being a professional in dentistry means. We have learned to be mindful of our behaviors  both within and outside of the dental community. I think it is important to be cognizant that as a dentist the public will perceive me as a leader/ role-model and that I should do my best play the part and act professionally.

My mission at NYUCD is to not only obtain the knowledge to become a dentist but to also obtain as much clinical practice as possible. I want to develop and fine tune the mechanical skills required by a dentist till I feel confident enough to work independently as a dentist outside NYUCD.  I want to become professionally competent and be able to efficiently self assess and evaluate.

With knowledge comes more power. I was once told knowledgable people are the most dangerous and I partially believe that statement. Many people teetered the line of ethics to get into dental school, and no doubt some will continue to do so will throughout school. I do hope that this teetering of the ethical boundary will not bleed into other areas, especially when the time comes to manage patients.

School is a priority, always is. But I must keep in mind why I chose this school and why I chose to live in this city. I accepted the rare opportunity to live in NYC during my youth and I need to take advantage of what this city can offer me.

I've worked quite hard to dig myself out of the hole I was in. Now I get to start fresh with a clean slate. This is a new beginning, but I can't forget what I sacrificed to get here. I am no longer doing this just for myself anymore.

Becoming a professional is a long and hard process. It does not only involve learning the theory behind the work but also how to act and maintain the responsibilities of a professional. To become a professional means to develop a network of other professionals in order to successfully treat those in your care.

I've been thrown into a world of professionalism recently, and it has been quite overwhelming. I had many people talk at me on what it is to be a professional and how to go about it. At this point, this start of my journey, all I can do is listen and heed the advice given to me.

I want to pass boards on first try. Stay friendly, easy going, and personable so that others may reach out to me if they have the wild idea to do so. I want to be competent and professional when dealing and treating patients. To develop good bedside manners. Have impact on teens/children not only in local areas but internationally too. I want to find my niche in my class, the school of dentistry and in my profession.

I hope I will become an individual who has the knowledge and skill to diagnose, develop treatment plans and perform the dental treatments successfully for my patients, or know how to provide referrals if outside of my capacity. Also I hope to have the skills to communicate  effectively with other health professionals to provide the best care for my patient. I will also carry out the proper boundaries, and keep patient information confidential. Outside of clinical settings, I will also maintain my moral and ethics. I also hope I will be able to participate on outreach programs to provide services and education to the communities locally, nationally, and globally.

My goal after 4 years at NYUCD is to master the didactic knowledge and practical skills in the field of dentistry, and to become a competent dental professional. Besides learning, I would also join multiple organizations to develop my leadership skills and to enrich my overall experience. In addition, apart from getting exposure to the clinical settings in NYUCD, I hope to actively get involved in various community outreach programs, both locally and internationally to help myself to develop communication skills with the patients and to achieve the professional competency I am expecting myself to become. Last but not least, I hope to develop positive working relationships with faculties and classmates to help me success in my future career.

Upon completion of dental school, I expect to be proficient in the classroom material and chair-side skills taught to me by the NYUCD faculty. Through development of cohesive relationships in clinics, I can best prepare myself to begin a dental career. Maximizing my exposure to research environments and techniques will provide a strong resume for acceptance into the specialty residency of my preference. I am determined to polish my professional skills for peer and patient interaction. Most importantly, I plan to enjoy my time in dental school and to provide the care and attention that my husband and son need.

After working in many areas of dentistry I realized I would really like to specialize in pediatric dentistry. To me dentistry is being able to give the gift of confidence, comfort and care. I believe if I can make any impact on a child to feel more confident, happy and comfortable that is one less worry in that child’s life. And that child will one day become an adult who does not fear a dentist and that adult will have good oral hygiene that was taught when their were a child.

In the next four years in NYUCD I want to not only have the knowledge of dentistry but, also be able to apply in in every step along the way. I want to know not only the standard procedures, but also alternative ways as different situations may come up. I want to provide professional care while being able to comfort the patient. I want to be able to work in every field/specialty of dentistry although I do want to specialize. I also plan on participating in many clubs and as many outreach programs as I can. I want to network with many different dental and medical professionals to be able to give patients the ultimate care. I want to be successful student as well as a successful health care provider.

While I'm at NYUCD I aim to be proficient and competent in the field of dentistry and to achieve a level of knowledge and mastery of skills in all components of the field allowing me to be confident in quality patient care.  I hope to be able to develop social working relationships with my group, and be able to give and receive constructive criticism to continually improve. As I work to become a dentist I hope to give back to the community by participating in outreach and volunteer programs.

I like to think that through the small jobs and experiences I have had, I have grown as a professional. However, I hope that being at NYUCD will help me become an even stronger professional in different aspects. Such aspects include: how to speak with patients, the type of language I use with my colleagues, mentors, and faculty, the type of attire, etc. I am looking forward to understanding what it takes to become a competent health professional.

I am hoping that dental school will help me gain as much knowledge as possible in each of the dental fields, especially since my current plan is to become a general dentist. Throughout the years I hope to gather as much knowledge about the different fields to help me decide whether I would like to pursue a career more specialized after the three years and ten months. One of my other major goals is to help out the community by participating in a community outreach program internationally during my D3 or D4 year. I also hope to not just focus on my studies but have the time to participate in clubs and student-run activities in order to network and meet my fellow colleagues as well as faculty members. In addition, with the many different people I will be meeting, I hope to enhance my social skills, form bonds, and create strong patient-doctor relationships.

Besides doing well academically here at NYUCD I also want to be financially comfortable so I can provide for my family and take care of my needs once I graduate. I want to learn what it takes to be successful in all areas of dentistry. Also, I want to be a part of local outreaches that NYU is involved in, because due to the fact that I am jewish I am unable to participate in the outreaches that are out the country, but I know that I can definitely be a part of the local ones. I've always wanted to be involved in outreaches especially when it involves this field and I looking forward to being part of them here at NYUCD.

My expectation as a dental student is not only to become a professionally competent health care professional who can provide quality care to patients with a variety of oral conditions, but to help patients with their needs aside from dentistry. To do this I believe it is important to listen to the patient’s problems thoroughly, and ask follow up questions so the patient can see that I am there to help them with their needs to the best of my ability. Also as a dental student I feel its important to do outreach’s and I plan to do that so I can feel the reinforcement that follows after such an amazing experience. I know that at NYUCD I will learn to master the skill of dentistry as a whole meaning that I will gain the manual dexterity, and clinical experience as well as patient interaction. Furthermore, I wish to achieve a personal relationship with my peers and the faculty at NYU which is extremely important. Finally, I wish to do very well in NYUCD academically, and become a successful dentist with my peers that I started my dental career with.

I want to display professional competency in dentistry and exude confidence. I want to better express myself in conversation, allowing me to forge meaningful relationships with others — not only with patients, but with coworkers and friends. This starts with hard work and ends with gaining confidence in my own abilities and knowledge. I want to gain confidence in my leadership abilities. I want to master dentistry, an endless road starting in D1.

Personally, I would like to specialize in fields such as orthodontics and pediatric dentistry since I want to study dentistry more in depth. I am interested in pediatric field since my mother is a pediatrician and I believe that it is always good to treat children. Beyond these, I would like to be more active as a person and interact with different people throughout my life in dental school.

Personally I would like to learn many things from dental school. I wish I could learn how to act like a professional and how to treat patients with delicate techniques that I would learn in dental school in near future. Eventually I wish I would apply things that I learn from dental school to community service that I wish to participate in after I graduate from dental school.

Becoming a professional is something that doesn't happen overnight. Professionals to me are those people that have a strong foundation of knowledge and master the skills and techniques of a specific trade. They have specific training in their field and are admired or trusted by the public to perform their that job for which they are trained. A professional is someone who acts according to ethical standards and abides to a set of specific legal guidelines. Working to become a professional will require devotion of many hours, days, weeks and years practicing my craft. I hope to become a trusted dental practitioner and the best professional I can be.

Over the next four years I hope to grow as a person. I want to learn and develop the skills I need in order to give the best possible care to all my future patients.  I hope to build and develop strong interpersonal relationships with my peers, faculty and future patients. I also hope to learn more about other cultures and ways of life to be able to better understand and communicate with a diverse patient population. I plan to become active within the College of Dentistry as well as the New York City community.

Over the next four years I hope to grow into a talented and compassionate dentist.  One of my personal goals is to not only become proficient but also more patient and compassionate.  I feel that these traits are essential to the practice of dentistry and to my overall goal of volunteering some of my time at a free dental clinic in an under served area.  A dentist in my college town did this, and after seeing how selfless he was and how much the community benefited from it, I knew I wanted to follow his example.  I am confident that the community here at NYUCD will help me foster these skills, and in doing so will benefit my classmates and my profession.  In order to be effective, dentists need to be approachable by patients and demonstrate compassion.

Over the next four years I hope to grow into a talented and compassionate dentist.  One of my personal goals is to not only become proficient but also more patient and compassionate.  I feel that these traits are essential to the practice of dentistry and to my overall goal of volunteering some of my time at a free dental clinic in an under served area.  A dentist in my college town did this, and after seeing how selfless he was and how much the community benefited from it, I knew I wanted to follow his example.  I am confident that the community here at NYUCD will help me foster these skills, and in doing so will benefit my classmates and my profession.

Although many medical professionals can do their work adequately, they also need to make sure that they can establish consoling roles and rapport with the patients. Furthermore, they need to make sure that they view the individual as a whole, rather than as a person with just a dental issue. I am certain that at my time at NYU, I will ultimately achieve my goal to be a successful medical professional. Not only will I learn about and treat diseases, I will also teach others on how to prevent them and promote oral hygiene as well. I will strive to establish one on one relationships with patients to eradicate the negative connotations associated with dentists. I will study hard and consume the most information that I can learn and apply them to reality to best suit my patients and peers. I hope to engage in extracurricular activities and outreach programs that will help me grow and develop into a professional so I can identify my attributes and weaknesses. Becoming a dentist would be a consummation of my life long goal to help people maintain excellent dental hygiene.
