I believe one of the most important aspects of dentistry is the technical perfection. I want to absorb as much technique as possible, and get a good understanding of each and every field of dentistry to develop any interest in specific field I may encounter. Seeing as many patients as possible as a dental student is also my goal. I wish to learn how to treat various cases and work with different patients before I go out to the real field. I hope to establish meaningful relationships with my patients and everyone I work with. Meanwhile, I wish to constantly remind myself of the ultimate goal to serve and support patients and communities around me. I am very excited about rich outreach and volunteer opportunities that NYU provides to us. At the end of the road after four years, I want to be able to look back and say that I’ve had one of the greatest and meaningful investments in my life.

To me, becoming a healthcare professional is very exciting. For one, it is a position worthy of respect and admiration. I will be a leader in my community, a person capable of administering real and positive improvements. As cliche as it may sound, I will be in a position to help people who are in pain, often times in the matter of one office visit. Becoming a professional means a great deal to myself and my family, but above all, doing so means accepting the responsibilities- both positive and risky- that come along with being a leader.

I hope to build up my clinical proficiency as best and, ideally, quickly as possible in my four years at NYUCD. Personally, I seek to mature to the extent of finding and maintaining a standard of professionalism and excellence that I may bring to my patients on a daily basis. Finally, I look forward to utilizing my large class size by approaching it as an opportunity to network with as many peers and future colleagues as I can (delve into the existingNYUCD alumni base if possible).

I hope that upon completing dental school I have gained concrete clinical as well as social skills that allow me to expand my professional network and make me approachable to patients. With the rapid pace of our current society, I would like to stay up to date with the advances within the field and hope to gain confidence with the technology along the way. Considering the impact our overwhelming curriculum will have, I want to make my health a priority. I hope that as we progress through the academic year that our class maintains a sense of togetherness and that my peers find me to be a beneficial resource to any questions they may have.

It seemed to me that I had accomplished everything when I got accepted into the dental school, as it had been my greatest goal during my undergraduate years. Now that I am in the dental school, it is hard for me to conceptualize what I am about to face and how I will mature as a dentist. But if I can choose what kind of dentist I will become, I wish to be an ethical dentist who values the patients’ health as the first priority.

I hope to become a well-balanced dentist by the completion of NYU College of Dentistry. Besides working diligently on academics like many other peers plan to, I want to focus on improving my communication skills. Through the years of experiences with the professors, peers, and patients, I hope to learn how to better establish new relationships and to better respond to critical situations as a health care professional.

Although I know the next 4 years at NYUCD will be rigorous and tough, I still hope to have a lot of fun and build wonderful relationships with faculty members and my peers. I don't plan to specialize, but I would like to participate in research that helps to improve the oral health of our society and to keep up with the rapidly advancing science and technology. I also hope to participate in one of the outreach programs offered at NYUCD to bring awareness to our community how important oral health is and also to appreciate all the wonderful opportunities and resources that I have. I want to gain enough experience and knowledge in dentistry so that I can be prepared to professionally work with various patients and cases on my own.

As of entering D1, there are more areas that I am not competent in than in areas that I am. There will be many obstacles and struggles along the way, but I am not afraid to make mistakes and I will try to learn as much as possible from the mistakes that I made so that I will not repeat them again. I believe that gaining a plenty of experience and knowledge is a key to becoming a competent and professional healthcare provider and I hope to reach that by the end of the 4 years at NYUCD.

I hope to be a competent and professional healthcare provider who is capable of communicating with her patients in an effective and understandable manner. I hope to feel more confident in carrying out challenging tasks that I may face in the future with my patients by gaining enough experience and knowledge in dentistry during the 4 years at NYUCD.

By the end of 4 years at NYUCD, I hope to be a professional and competent dentist who is not only able to carry out any challenging procedure proficiently, but also an approachable healthcare provider who her patients can trust and rely on. Not only do I wish to be successful academically, but I also hope to build wonderful relationships with faculty members and fellow classmates.

Over the next four years, my goal is to become an excellent dental practitioner who is dedicated to giving my patients the best care possible. Through NYUCD, I will develop my leadership and interpersonal skills so that I can effectively communicate and build positive relationships with my colleagues and patients. I’ve been given such a great opportunity in being able to study at this school and I will strive everyday to gain as much knowledge and build my manual dexterity so that I can mold myself into a competent doctor. I also aim to be active in the dental community throughout the next four years so that I can continue to do so in the future.

I hope to gain confidence and self-trust in my skill as a dentist throughout my 4 years as a student at NYUCD. I hope to build a strong network of support that extends beyond my life as a student, and into my life as a dental professional. I hope to have strengthened my communication skills in order to be able to effectively interact with patients and colleagues of diverse cultural backgrounds and of varying lifestyles. I hope to create lasting relationships with the faculty and students in such a large student body. Lastly, I hope to utilize the strength of NYUCD's clinical facilities and resources in order to become the most proficient healthcare provider that I can be.

One of the competencies a professional requires is integrity. To display integrity, it is required that one stands up for their own values and beliefs, despite its opposition and difficulty. I feel that integrity allows one to act as a role model with an increased sense of ethical and moral principles. Ethics is the adherence to legal and societal constraints, which promotes honesty and trustworthiness within the field of dentistry.

I chose NYUCD for the diverse patient pool and strong clinical facilities. Through my short time here, I am beginning to realize that I will enjoy my stay here, due to the warm and welcoming faculty that want nothing more than our success. I am aware of the wide range of research opportunities and will love to take part in summer internships or working in other labs during D3 and D4. Coming from McMaster University's Biochemistry program, I know that I have the strong foundation to take on the duties in research. 
I also strive to build strong relationships with my peers and faculty. I realize the importance of networking and I am willing to  make an effort to connect with others to make my experience here at NYUCD the best it can be.

Becoming a professional is more than just receiving a DDS. I know that professionals need to develop the necessary inter-personal skills to be able to most effectively connect with patients on a personal level. I feel that through this, there is a more significant and long-lasting impact that will better the lives of every patient, both mentally and physically. Professionals are role models in society, where the general population looks at one group of people for their health and well being. The responsibilities of becoming a professional are large, and I have a strong feeling that my effort in addition to the opportunities that NYUCD provides will enable me to become the best I can be.

Becoming a professional requires much more than the completion of requirements towards a degree. I feel that professionals exhibit the competencies of sensitivity, self-control, tact and diplomacy, integrity, judgmental analysis, conscientiousness, and communication. Sensitivity involves the deliberate action of attempting to understand other viewpoints or situations, not just the identification of differences. Making wise and rational decisions under stressful situations defines self-control. The ability to build and maintain friendly and stimulating relationships, whilst considering differences in culture and values displays tact and diplomacy. Integrity is the competency of fighting for the principles and beliefs, even in situations where it is difficult to do so. Through the assessment of situations in defining the problem, judgmental analysis is exhibited through critical analysis, prioritization, and creativeness. To be conscientiousness, the professional needs to be enthusiastic and committed to the love for dentistry. Finally, communication requires the professional to be a compelling, honest, and articulate oral communicator.

In dental school and my future career in dentistry, I strive for continual self-improvement and forward development. I will apply my previous volunteer experiences, along with my newfound knowledge to interact and connect with patients on a personal level. Moreover, the strong clinical training that NYUCD offers will enable me to provide exceptional oral healthcare with the highest proficiency and quality. I aim to embody the mindset that dentists are not only healthcare providers, but also trusted members of society - viewed as companions and advisors. I know that this profession requires much more than academic excellence; it involves manual dexterity skills, attention to detail, critical thinking, and the communication skill set required to educate patients on the significance of oral care and hygiene. My contributions to society will not be limited to providing outstanding oral healthcare services to the general public, as I intend to broaden my scope of care to aid the less fortunate populations. I strongly believe that NYUCD will provide me with the opportunities to gain experience through outreach programs. NYUCD is my avenue towards achieving my goals. I am focused and ready to begin.

While at NYUCD I hope to pursue my interest in research. During my undergraduate career I was a part of a few research groups and enjoyed the experience, and therefore I would like to participate in research that is specific to dentistry. Additionally, I would like to get a feel for the various dental specialties in order to decide whether specializing is right for me.

My goal at NYUCD is to become a competent dentist. In order to achieve this goal I will need to develop my interpersonal skills so that I can treat patients to the best of my ability. Furthermore, I would like to develop a support network of both peers and faculty with the hope that they can help me accomplish my goal. Lastly, I hope to develop the technical skills required to be a competent dentist.

In order to become a professional, I must evaluate all of my strengths and weakness. As future primary health care providers, it is our duty to constantly improve ourselves so that we can refine our services given to our patients. Also, before I can treat the patients as a dentist, I must learn all of the material given in our didactic classes and clinical simulation labs. I need to be an excellent student before I can become a professional dentist. Overall, I must improve myself so that I can help the public improve their oral health.

Over the next four years, I strive to become a dedicated practitioner who is focused on the best interests of the patient. Not only will I attempt to fully learn all of the science based knowledge in the didactic classes, but I will also develop my interpersonal skills to better communicate with my colleagues, mentors, and patients. I need to become an excellent provider for dental health which can be achieved by developing my technical proficiency and following ethical procedures. In addition, I wish to become a role model and educator for the community so I can eliminate the stigma that dentistry is an occupation associated with pain and replace it with the ideology of preventative treatment. Overall, I am looking to improve myself as a person and as a future dentist.

During the next four years I seek to become a mature and skilled professional who puts the care of the patient at the forefront of all goals. I would like to become a well rounded individual who is not only knowledgeable about dentistry, but healthcare as a whole. I seek to have fun while building relationships with my colleagues that will hopefully carry over into my post-NYU years. Lastly, I would to invest all of my resources and strength into the NYU community and hopefully receive the same in return.

I seek to have fun while building relationships with my colleagues that will hopefully carry over into my post-NYU years. It is my hope to achieve continued growth and self-improvement by overcoming the daunting academic challenges of dental school and through peer evaluation. I will develop the confidence as well as the knowledge necessary to competently treat patients in a professional setting.  It is important to me to get involved in the community by taking advantage of exciting local and global outreach opportunities, so that I may be instilled with the values and passion an empathic and professional dentist would have. Lastly, I want to build lasting and meaningful relationships with my peers in order to cultivate a communal sense of trust and respect.

I think that graduating a dental school does not necessary mean becoming a professional.  Instead, becoming a health professional seems to becoming a person who can provide community with positive influences in efficient and appropriate manner.  In order to gain such skills, I believe that I should understand what my strengths and weaknesses are, and look for ways to develop as more mature and competent individual through careful and critical self-assessments and peer-assessments.

Through my years at NYUCD, I hope that I will be able to acquire not only the academic knowledge and clinical skills but also various interpersonal skills.  I believe that a number of extracurricular programs offered by the school including various outreach programs will help me to improve my skills to communicate well, express empathy effectively, establish a rapport with patients, and collaborate with peers as a team.  At the end of my dental education at NYUCD, I wish I will be a competent dentist who is able to provide the community with best quality dental and oral health care.

As a dental professional, I will be an engaged and competent individual that society can count on to help them make well informed decisions about their oral health. I believe that professionalism does not end upon exiting the office and that a true professional should hold himself to a higher set of standards even outside the office.

During my time at NYUCD, I will look to building a solid foundation that will allow me to become a competent dentist. By acquiring a large amount of knowledge and skills, I aspire to be able to help patients manage their oral health through educating and effectively treating them. I am excited for the opportunities to learn, meet new people, and give back to my community.

Being a professional in the dental field has many components; it requires compassion, technical excellence, clinical knowledge, and the ability to know what's best for patients and execute it in the most effective way possible. Through didactic courses as well as clinical, hands-on experience, I will be able to learn what is the best course of treatment for my patients. Working with my peers in this journey will help me become a professional, as dentistry requires collaboration and teamwork between peers. Dental school will help me practice and develop these skills, and enable me to become a competent professional.

My goal is to become an excellent clinical dentist by developing my manual dexterity, learning how to communicate effectively with my patients and learning to make the best decisions in their individual treatment. I aim to be very involved in the NYU community, in order to develop meaningful relationships with faculty members and peers, and be an active, contributing participant in our collective dental school journey. Participating in a variety of activities will allow me to interact with many different people, and provide a productive outlet outside academics. I will challenge myself in learning as much as I can in the basic medical sciences, as this will help me provide excellent, whole-body centered care to my patients.

My goal for these next 4 years at NYU is to develop into a competent dentist, proficient in all aspects of dentistry. I hope to learn how to efficiently communicate and interact with patients to provide them with a level of understanding that will allow them to make informed decisions regarding their oral health. I am anxious to participate in outreach opportunities both global and domestic that will enable me to make an impact on the community and hopefully inspire others to continue to bridge the gap in access to dental care. Upon graduation I would like to have developed lifelong friendships that I will truly value for the rest of my life.

After shadowing a pediatric dentist for almost half a year, I have developed a strong affinity for pediatric dentistry. As the years go by in my academic career I would like to better myself in preparation for a career in dentistry. I will push myself so that I can be successful in providing a service to my community.

In the next four years of dental school, I want to develop as many relationships as possible through networking. These relationships will be at a personal friendship level, but will also be professional as future colleagues. In terms of personal skills, I hope to improve on my own dexterity and become a very efficient worker. Patient interaction is something I am looking forward to, and I hope that at the end of my fourth year, my patients will not only be able to trust me professionally, but also personally as well.  Not only do I want to be able to gain knowledge through the courses, but I also want to excel in them. I hope to be an example of what a professional dentist is defined as.
I want to make the most of the time I spend here by doing the best I can in academia as well as in areas of life outside of school.
I want to make the most of the time I spend here by doing the best I can in academia as well as in areas of life outside of school.

As I become a competent dentist, I also want to continue building physical endurance and strength to better serve my country as a US army soldier and dentist; Therefore, I hope to improve upon my time management skills in order to exceed professional, personal, and military expectations.

I am committed to become a competent dentist that genuinely cares about patients. Also, I  want to be active in my community and participate in outreach programs. Last but not least, I expect to join a research program at NYUCD.

The ethics course we have this semester has been a very interesting exposure to possible problems that dentist can encounter in the field and has been a good jumping off point to start thinking about how I would personally react and perform in these challenging scenarios. For example, what would you do in a situation in which you accidentally nick the patient's gums but they are under anesthetic and are unaware of this happening, or what do you do if the treatment plan the son prefers differs from the treatment plan his very elderly father would like for himself.

Beyond a career in dentistry I hope to be able to continue becoming a well rounded individual in all aspects of my professional and personal life. I think it is very inspirational when I come across professors that have lived such interesting lives and have great stores to tell. Today Ronaldo Hirata gave a lecture on amalgam and at the end he included a quote from a poem that said something like; tell your story to the wind, life is not worth living if you don't have a story to tell' and I hope my life will live up to this.

Having been in dental school for just two months, I am already starting to see a shift in people's reactions when I tell them that I am in school to become a dentist and it becomes more apparent of the responsibilities attached to our degree. I hope that as the year progresses, I can continue to gain the skills to meet these expectations.

I hope to become a health care provider that my patients and other professionals are able to trust and turn to for advice. Ultimately I hope to develop a strong relationship with my patients wherein I am able to treat families throughout different generations.

Just in the past two months alone, I feel like I have learned so much to prepare me for my dental career. Most of our classes are focused in foundational courses but courses like GDS lab where we have learned how to do wax-ups, do class I and class II preps and composite and amalgam fillings have been very beneficial to get exposed to early. I would really like to solidify and become confident in these basic skills so I can start building on this foundation as the year progresses.

I hope to gain a solid foundation in the sciences and develop confidence in my technical skills while acquiring a deeper understanding of the business side of dentistry. Ultimately, I hope to be able to communicate effectively with future patients and colleagues and gain their trust in my abilities. Furthermore, I hope to develop a strong relationship with my peers, advisers, and professors that extends beyond the four years of dental school.

Ethical reflection is an essential goal of education. Ethical reflection is the foundation in every professional. Professionals should apply their knowledge of moral decision making and choosing the option that enhances themselves as competent professionals. In the field of dentistry, patients place trust and responsibility under the professional. The dentist should be fully dedicated in making the patient experience the best health care from the dentist.

Creating a great relationship with the NYUCD community will further enhance my ability to become a competent dentist. I will learn from the faculty as well as create relationships that will last a lifetime.

I feel that in order to become a professional I need to advance myself not only in my skills as a future dentist my also my skills as future business owner, as a future mentor to others and as future person who can communicate and get along with his fellow peers. These three aspects are needed to make oneself a overall well rounded dentist that contribute to his patients not only via his or her dental procedures but also can contribute to his patients feeling confident in the dental practice they go to and confident in the dentist that operates on them.

My goal in dental school is to come out as fully competent dentist. I will try to obtain attributes that would allow me not only to understand the science and procedures in dentistry but also allow me to develop social and personal skills. My mission is too understand dentistry in every single aspect so that when I am working with a patient I can make them fully aware of what is going on during a procedure. To obtain these attributes I will try to use every opportunity that NYU offers during the next four years, opportunities ranging from community outreach, club organizations and the great faculty that always are willing to help students. Ultimately during the next four years I want to come out as a well rounded dentist.

A major part of being a professional involves upholding certain ethical and moral obligations. I feel that as a dentist, I will constantly have my personal opinions clash with what is generally accepted by the general public. To avoid any subjective actions, I wish to follow a moral code in order make the best decision possible. This includes learning the certain ethics involved in treating patients as I want to be as fair as I can as my decision-making. By following ethical procedures, I will be able to provide moral propositions and a practical means of determining a course of action when deciding whether something is right or wrong.

In order to be professional, I feel I have to be qualified and capable of carrying out the duties entrusted to me.  There will be certain standards that are expected of me as I am trained to have the necessary skills to carry out my designated role. As a dental professional, I am responsible for the health of others, thus I must uphold certain ethical and moral obligations. I also must be competent and proficient in treating my patients since as a professional dentist, I will be entrusted to have the knowledge and expertise necessary to provide the best oral health care for everyone.

As an aspiring dentist, it is my mission to constantly improve myself in dental school, whether in clinic or in studies, in order to be able to provide the best care for my future patients. I strive to be an independent, diligent, patient, and reliable dentist. I will never forget that I am a medical professional who is entrusted with the skill and responsibility to provide the best dental care for the greater community, thus I will be conscious of all of my actions as I want to uphold the integrity of being a provider of oral health care as a dentist. I will always be mindful, respectful and kind to others, whether it be my peers, mentors, faculty, or patients as I want to create a pleasant environment for everyone to be in. I am always open to advice or constructive criticism as I entered dental school with the mindset of tackling all my weakness and becoming a better person and professional dentist.
Being ethical has a lot to do with honesty, but also in stretching yourself to being the best that you can be.
I want to find a residency program that both excites and suits me.
Being a professional to me means conducting oneself to a certain standard at all times. You are in a highly scrutinized field and I intend to live up to the expectation.
Being a professional entails a high standard of academic integrity and communicating to others in a concise and respectful manner at all times.
Thus far, we are still undertaking the professionalism and ethics course, but I feel that we are learning a lot.

My four years will be dedicated to practicing and building the skills necessary to become a proficient and competent dentist. I will work to become a well-rounded professional, eager and capable of assisting others in need.

Stepping into the role of a professional will require me to constantly be looking for ways to improve my knowledge and skills. It will mean learning a whole new language for dealing with other health care professionals and understanding the relationship between doctors and patients. But most importantly it's a title that requires me to live up to a higher standard both in and out of the clinic.

At my completion of dental school I plan to be wholly confident in the dental skills I have acquired and have a solid understanding of the science backing those skills. I will be able to build positive successful relationships based on respect with my patients, colleagues, and team members. That I will have a plan in place to continue my dental education after graduation, and have a strong knowledge base about joining and starting a dental practice. I will have outreach incorporated into my future practice, and have a clear ethical code by which my staff and I abide.

I hope to develop into a competent professional throughout my experiences at the dental school. A professional is not merely one who knows the procedures and tools of his trades, a professional must also act his part and be able to communicate his duties to his patients. By observing the interactions and relationships between the dentists and their patients in the clinic, I hope to be able to observe and mirror the relationships I see. By attending research conferences, I hope to observe and learn the ways that professionals present their work to their communities. Community outreach further develops one into a professional because one is responsible to representing his entire field and line of work.

As an aspiring dentist, I would like to ensure that I am professional and competent at performing dental procedures in a timely and nearly flawless manner. I would like to maintain a clear path of communication with patients and attempt to destroy the stigma of a dental visit being a scary, painful and ruthless experience. I would like to serve my community by volunteering my services and encouraging people to seek dental care not only during urgent situations but making it a routine part of life as a preventative measure. 
	As members of the same field, interactions between professionals will be essential and vital to our success in the field.  One of the most important relationships in my future will be between myself and my future patients. I would like to ensure that they will be fully comfortable with me performing dental procedures. Over the next four years, I will observe many different patient-doctor interactions and learn from them the best ways to ease the fear of patients and educate about the procedures being performing.

Going forward in dental school I aim to be able to deliver comprehensive dental care to a variety of communities and improve myself professionally as well as clinically. I will strive to be engaged in the school student body as well the city around us and utilize the peer and mentor resources available to augment my abilities as a student and a future dentist. In the future I hope to be able to practice as a pediatric dentist, being able to provide preventative and therapeutic care for the youth as well as instill healthy dental practices in their lives as they develop into adults.

I expect that my experiences through four years of school will guide me in becoming a dental professional. Things such as self assessment and peer assessment will allow me to see points of improvement and how to gain the empathy, ethics, and skills needed. Utilizing peer support, peer mentors, and faculty advisors will give me a similar such perspective on how to improve. I expect that simply working in the pre-clinical and clinical settings with my GPD group will allow me to gain the necessary professional competence. Going through experiences with actual patients will make me be able to realize how I've improved or gained professional skills. Those skills can again be reviewed by coworkers and peers that are giving me feedback on it. Technically, exams and evaluations will provide the actual feedback on my professional performance.

Being an ethical dentist is very important as there are numerous ways to be unethical.  In the dentistry field there are temptations to charge too much, say a patient needs a procedure when they dont, say a job is complete when we know its not, and many other scenarios.  Ethics has always been an important moral in my life.  In my humble opinion, the world is corrupt with unethical decisions from competent professionals.  These masters of their fields can go about completing half-finished and faulty work without anyone every questioning them.  To me, we will be making enough money to support our families while taking the time to treat each patient correctly.  There is no reason to perform halfhearted work in the sake of seeing more patients.  I hope to keep true to these morals, even when faced with a hard decision somewhere down the road.

Besides what was said in the public reflection, it is extremely important for me to find a career which will allow me to be a provider for my future family. As an individual, I want to improve my communication skills, create long-lasting and strong relationships and friendships with my classmates, and become a stronger and better person overall, inside and outside my profession. Becoming a professional will take time because I will need to establish knowledge and adequate inter-personal skills to communicate effectively with my patients. As a a dentist, I want to impact peoples oral health by setting a good example, being an approachable dentist and individual, creating a comfortable environment for patients, and being a genuine professional with full competency. I hope to gain excellent skills and also do well enough academically that any specialization option is open to me. I also hope to determine for sure what specialty (if any) is best for me

During the years I spend in dental school, there are several goals I would like to accomplish. Obviously the main goal for everyone is to become a technically excellent dentist and have the skills to provide all the services patients need. Also I would like to do well in academic classes. Specifically I want to improve my study skills, such as avoiding procrastination and overcoming test anxiety. Also I want to make sure that the information I learn becomes part of my long-term memory, and is not forgotten once a class ends. I am not currently planning to specialize, but doing well academically would keep those options open. I hope that learning, especially in clinic during D3 and D4 years, will help me decide for sure what path in dentistry I want to take, such as research. A long-term goal I have is to improve the public perception of dentists as much as one person can, and I hope during dental school I can do this by helping my patients not feel nervous around a dentist, and not dread coming back. I hope NYU makes me a great dentist.

Becoming a dental professional requires gaining the necessary foundational knowledge and experiences. I hope to gain this knowledge, experience and skill through basic science classes and labs, pre-clinical labs, clinics, hospital rotations, and local and global outreaches. 
Through exams and competencies, as well as feedback from peers and advisers, I hope to be evaluated and measured as a competent professional.

My goal is to take advantage of the academic, clinical and social resources available at the school in order to become a skilled, well-rounded and competent oral health care professional dedicated to treating, raising awareness, educating and improving the overall health and quality of life of the local and global community.
      Along the way, I will strive to develop strong personal and professional relationships that have a positive impact in my life as well as in the field of dentistry.

One of the biggest reasons why I chose the dental profession is due to the financial security it provides. I want a job that will make enough money and provide enough free time that I will be able to properly take care of my parents as they get older. My parents have always been there to motivate me even when times may have seem very bleak. I will work hard these next four years to make my parents proud because nothing would make me happier than to see my parents finally be able to relax and enjoy their lives instead of working day in and day out to provide for me.

Being a professional means that I have to realize that I must put the patients wellbeing as my top priority. What this means is that I must always maintain my curiosity in my field and always strive to keep up to date with the current literature. As a dental professional, a patient puts a great deal of trust upon the dentist since dental treatments may lead to unchangeable results. With this in mind, I understand that becoming a professional does not only include being proficient in your manual and intellectual skills, but also the ability to be consistent and always provide the highest level of care.

I hope that during my stay here at NYUCD I will be able gain the skills and expertise to become the best healthcare provider I can possibly be. I will strive to always push myself to my full potential as I want to be able to provide the best possible service to all my future patients. In addition I wish to build a network of friends and colleagues whom I can rely and trust on. Finally, I hope to discover and learn more about myself during these next defining years of my life.

I want to build good connections with people, whether they are dental students, dentists, professors or other people that I meet in NYC. I also hope that I can set up my practice in the west coast in the future. Most importantly, I want to learn as much as possible in school and be an excellent dentist after four years. I want to know my own limit. I always feel like I can achieve more in my life but I always make up excuses of not doing it.

Professionalism is being able to deliver competent treatment to the patients while being able to demonstrate integrity, accountability, respects and fairness during the procedures and the communications with the patients. Furthermore, professionalism also applies outside of clinic when dentists interact with other individuals. Professionalism could not be achieved in a short period of time. It requires the teaching from the supervisors and self-reflections of the students.

I want to be a competent dentist who can deliver excellent work to my patients and being able to communicate with my patients. I want to balance my time between school works and social lives; therefore, I need to work on my time management skills so that I can finish my tasks, studies, assignments on time while having time to participate other activities outside of school. I am also interested in community outreach programs and I hope that I will have the opportunities to participate in them in my free time.

As a person in the future, I want to combine the career of oral surgery and being a father, husband, and person.  I want to use the lessons I learned from my travels, which is basically the power of patience, meditation, clear and present mind, calmness, purpose, and adventure.  I think medicine is fun and satisfying and I can do a lot with my field.  I wouldnt necessarily just call myself a healthcare provider at that level, but rather someone who can deliver wisdom and pull them out too ;)

Being a professional means to me that I can handle being a healthcare provider and someone that people look up to and follow by example.  What I take from it is what i want to teach my children and the younger generation about the lifestyle you live and how to maintain good morals and good social standards.  Having the ability to look at what you do in a third person perspective is important in establishing my role as a professional.  Also, it means having a duty, which is a responsibility to play my role in society, I have a special niche and must fulfill that role.

As a professional, I am expected to maintain a proper work ethic and personal behavior.  Part of profssionalism is leadership and leading by example.  It is important to keep your personaility and life structure consistent in all aspect of your life such as home, work, even going to the mall.  As a professional, people rely on you as someone who is capable of doing their job and the most elite level and doing it well.  At no point can a professional be any less competent in their mental state of mind (of course there is the human aspect which allows for some slack).

My goals as a dentist is to be able to make an impact.  I want to acheieve the highest level of medicine for two reasons: Self fulfillment and to have the priviledge to help others.  My plan is to pursue an Oral Surgery path so that I can cure, prevent, and treat at the highest level possible for people that need any type of service.  Eventually I would settle in various parts of the country and the world and establish practices that will expand and provide all sorts of healthcare to the community that surrounds it.

Within these next four years at NYUCD, I hope to gain a full understanding of dentistry through both a didactic and a clinical setting. My goal is to be able to integrate these skills to become a competent dentist that can provide excellent healthcare to my patients. I hope to learn from and grow with my peers for the next four years, establishing life-long friendships, to become a compassionate, trustworthy dentist to a diverse population of patients. I want to participate in multiple local and global outreach programs, to gain the knowledge and experience needed to treat patients and educate them on the importance of oral healthcare. Through these next four years, I hope to find what I'm most passionate for, whether that be general dentistry or specializing in pediatrics.

To become a professional, I hope to be able to transform the knowledge I have gained from didactic courses, and technical skills in pre-clinic into the clinic when working with real patients. Within these next years, self-assessment and getting peer feedback is an important aspect to always look at so that I can improve myself in aspects of dentistry, in order to become a professional. Interactions and communication with colleagues and patients is also a key. This helps to learn how to become an understanding professional who knows how to achieve their patients needs and communicate in an effective manner.

To become a professional, I believe you need to be able to transform everything learned in the didactic courses and pre-clinic into the clinical setting. With the ability to self-assess, and receive peer feedback, we can continue to strive to improve ourselves and the treatment of patients in a professionally competent way. In order to become a compassionate, understanding professional, constant interactions among a diverse group of colleagues and patients is necessary. Being a well-rounded individual in knowledge, technical skills, and communication is key to becoming a professional.

Within these next four years at NYUCD, I hope to gain a full understanding of dentistry through both a didactic and a clinical setting. My goal is to be able to integrate these skills to become a competent dentist that can provide excellent healthcare to my patients. I hope to learn from and grow with my peers for the next four years, establishing life-long friendships, to become a compassionate, trustworthy dentist to a diverse population of patients. I want to participate in multiple local and global outreach programs, to gain the knowledge and experience needed to treat patients and educate them on the importance of oral healthcare.

I would like to fully integrate myself into NYUCD both academically clinically, and socially, while creating my own personal niche in the school and profession.  I hope to further develop my leadership skills and to gain professional confidence in order to foster positive and lasting relationships with both my peers and patients. I plain on maintaining my involvement in research and getting involved in local and global communities to help impact individuals and the field of dentistry in a unique way. I anticipate building the foundation of a career that will bring me happiness and success throughout my life in and out of a dental office.

I believe that we are all products of our environment and through my experience in dental school, labs, and clinics becoming a professional wil begin to come naturally. Currently, we are sort of "faking it til we make it" and playing the role. I know how to dress, speak, and act professionally in a general sense, however, dental school will teach me how to be a dental professional, specifically. The progression of participating in lab and then clinics, as well as involvement in the community and leadership roles will help facilitate the transition to being a true and competent professional.

Through NYUCD, I would hope to not only graduate with the knowledge, proficiency and competence to best treat patients, but to also have the support and networking of the NYU community. With the help of NYUCD, I aim to improve my communication skills with both my peers and patients in order to further my professional capability.
Aside from working hard during school, I would like to find the fine balance between studying for my academics with other social activities, such as school clubs and community service. Hopefully in the future, I can also hand down some advice to incoming students in order to assist them in discovering what to expect in dental school and how to utilize the programs that NYUCD offers.
With four years ahead of me, I will strive to improve myself constantly in order to become a better dentist and better person overall.

I look forward to learning science and skills in my course work that is applicable to patient care and clinical development. The different lab and clinical examinations I will experience will make me accustomed to the skills necessary for the oral health care profession. By being submersed in the dental profession and observing the professionals around me I will begin to pick up important traits that will be expected of me as a professional.  As my social life develops and by staying well rounded outside of class I will be able to grow and better assess my strengths and weaknesses through peer interactions. Most importantly I look forward to patient interaction and gaining the knowledge of dealing with individuals in a friendly way while conveying a high level of professionalism. Ultimately, by being a part of the program and challenging myself I will become a product of my environment.

I will strive to gain the professional competency and social skills to provide the best health care possible for my patients. I look forward to making great friendships both professionally and personally while growing as an individual during the next four years.

As a competent professional, I hope to always be committed to my patients and work to my utmost ability.  Ideally, I will make great personal accomplishments in the field of dentistry and always continue grow as a professional.

Certain principles that I hold of the utmost importance in my ethical beliefs are honesty, integrity, and humility. It is my duty to put the patient's best interest before mine for the simple fact that they come to me with a problem that they hope I will be able to resolve. In addition, it is imperative that as a practitioner, I do not take an authoritative stance while providing care for my patient, but rather focus on patient autonomy. This will allow the patient to intrinsically motivate themselves for change to better improve their oral health as well as the quality of their lives.

In order to be a true professional, I believe there is always room for improvement to enhance my skills as a competent and confident dental practitioner. Maintaining a professional appearance does not only come with the price of a shirt and tie, but understanding the importance of punctuality and quality in my work. These are the attributes I will strive to master throughout the next four years in an effort to better myself as a professional as well as a person.
Eager to start making some.

As a proud member of the NYUCD community, I am committed to providing the highest quality dental care to the global community with dedication, diligence, and utmost integrity through a family oriented oral health practice.

Being ethical means doing what is right. In the field of dentistry, we are dealing with humans as our patients and we should strive to always serve them best in our capacity. Maintaining strong ethical values is necessary to not only uphold the name of our profession, but also that of our school, NYUCD. If we do not have good ethics, patients would no longer choose to come to us for treatment.

Entering dental school, I have heard a lot about the struggle to keep up with coursework and also find time for leisurely activities. I hope to find the balance between both my coursework and free time, while remaining successful in both arenas. Since I have worked hard to get to dental school, I want to maintain a GPA I can be proud of and learn and absorb as much as possible.

Being a professional requires a great deal of skill in many arenas. It is not enough to have excellent manual skills or to dress in an appropriate manner. To be a true professional in the dental field, one must enhance their social skills and be able to effectively communicate with their patients. One should be able to demonstrate empathy and have a strong sense of ethics, while always treating both the patients and the healthcare team with dignity and respect.

My goal in dental school is to take advantage of all the opportunities provided and to work hard to receive an excellent dental education. Such opportunities include local and global outreach, leadership, and research. I want to develop a strong sense of professionalism and ethics, while also building strong personal relationships. After dental school, I hope to be an excellent practitioner, both in the clinical and social aspects, while remaining continually involved in community outreach.
I am committed to try my very best to learn and understand well all the ethical and regulatory code of conduct in the dental profession.

Besides my primal motivation to become a "good" doctor, I would love to have the opportunity to explore different activities outside of the classroom such as: international outreach and scientific research (my area of interest right now is oral cancer and biomaterial). Regarding specialty, I would love to have opportunity to explore the specialty of Endodontics and Oral Surgery.

In my opinion, becoming a professional goes hand-in-hand with taking great responsibility to your action and all the consequences that might follow. Particularly, a dental professional has to be willing to take responsibility to bring the best care for his/her patients, to lead his health care team, and to contribute to his/her community. A dental professional also have to show great empathy to his/her patients and the willingness to care for people. He/she also has to dedicate to his/her personal development and become a life-long learner in order to continuously perform at the highest level possible.

I am starting my journey into the world of professional health care. I know there will be lots of challenges and obstacles waiting for me to tackle, but I am greatly excited to take this one-in-a life time chance to grow personally and professionally.

Getting into dental school, I set myself with a single-minded goal to become "good" dentist. In my opinion, I define "good" dentist as a highly skilled and well-trained doctor who possesses a solid foundational knowledge both in basic sciences and clinical and is able to effectively implement his/her skill and knowledge in deliver best results for patients. "Good" doctor is also a great communicator and listener who shows great empathy to patients and has the utmost desire to serve people. That's the kind of dentist I am striving to become through my training and later in my professional life.

In order to act ethically we need to consider the moral question, or dilemma in order for us to act accordingly. We also need to consider who is going to be affected by our decisions, we may choose to do nothing and in many instances many will do nothing at all, we need to learn how to get passed that and understand that if we act ethically we may be judged by others in some occasions but we need to be able to let go, and do the right thing.
I would like to specialize in pediatrics or surgery , but that is something that is not for sure yet, I would like to experience general dentistry first and go on from there.

It will be hard for me to become a professional, because I always expect to excel at every single thing that I do. I consider myself an over achiever, but in dental school I will not be perfect, I will have many occasions in which I am wrong and I have to learn from my mistakes. I need to learn no to judge myself so harshly and  understand that with hard work I will become the professional i have always wanted to be.

Becoming a professional takes time, practice and hard work. There will be times when we might question ourselves and our capability of becoming professionals, but it is the drive and motivation, along with the skills (personal, didactical and practical) that we’ll learn at NYUCD not only from professors but from our classmates that will become competent professionals.
Nothing yet, we will se how the first year goes.

I hope to become a competent and skillful dentist. I want to learn how to act ethically and empathetically with my patients and my team.  I hope to become as resourceful as I can be in order to learn how to become a professional. Throughout my years at NYUCD I hope to learn how to become more organized and how to manage my time, also to learn how to assess myself and to accept criticism from myself and others as well, which in the end will help me as a professional in the future.

In my opinion, ethics is a big part of any healthcare profession. Honest and trust are big parts of ethics that I am going to build my relationship on toward my patients. I will always put my clients before any priority and hope to build a strong connection with them, so they can feel comfortable being around me.

I hope that NYUCD will give me the knowledge and skills needed in the field of dentistry to become a competent dentist. Coming out as a graduate in the next four years, I want to be mentally and physically prepared to give back to others in the community. Within my four years in NYUCD, I hope to join the outreach program and gain more experience working with a diverse amount of patients. I hope to keep on growing and learning as I continue my dental education at NYUCD.

Becoming a professional in the healthcare department is of one that is a learning process throughout one’s career. A healthcare professional is someone that accepts a challenge in his or her daily careers and handles the problem in a well-mannered way while learning something new.
As of now, I am eager to make some every year for the next four years in NYU dental school.

in this society, it becomes increasingly hard to distinguish what is right from the wrongs. it is hard enough to fight back with my own conscience and it is becoming harder than ever. I have spoken to many dentists and they are morally struggling when they have to choose between patients and money. I honestly don't know how to act morally if i were in their shoes.

being a dentist is my personal dream since childhood.
I have no idea what i want to achieve in this highly prestigious field. Maybe i am just doing it because my mind is unconsciously ordering me to do it. fortunately, i think that i don't have to worry about this at this moment. through out the orientation, surprisingly i have learned what i need to do and how i would achieve it.

becoming a dentist is a very long procedure. I must go through 4 years of school and that is just a beginning to be a competent profession. how harsh or rewarding it will be?? I have no clue.
I am just going to do it and hopefully it comes to me naturally as i strive in this to be one.

NYU college of dentistry is one of the largest dental school in the united states. we must understand it is not only the size but the quality that the school has built through out the history.
I will be honored to learn from the best faculty members with the support from administration.

I am planning on attending every single classes that is thrown at me in this institute. people say it is pretty hard to do that. I don't think nothing is impossible to do if i put my mind into it. by doing so, i will strengthen my academic foundation. after graduation, which i still have almost 4-years to go through, I am going to work at under-represented community and help people with no access to professional help

In the field of dentistry, I would like to grow into a competent doctor. it is sometimes hard to define what it means to be a good doctor. if i know that i am competent to not only dental procedures but also to the patients, my career will be much more professional.

My ultimate goals and ambitions as a future oral health care provider is to be sufficiently adept and proficient with the most current standard of care, so to provide adequate comprehensive care for my patient’s oral and more importantly systemic health.  Furthermore, attain a dynamic diverse social knowledge, so to provide a comfortable environment for which it will be conducive to all individuals equally.

My ultimate goals and ambitions as a future oral health care provider is to be sufficiently adept and proficient with the most current standard of care, so to provide adequate comprehensive care for my patient’s oral and more importantly systemic health.  Furthermore, attain a dynamic diverse social knowledge, so to provide a comfortable environment for which it will be conducive to all individuals equally.

I believe that part of being a professional involves making moral decisions that may or may not change a person's life. I feel that one must strive for the best course of outcome while thinking of the greater good falls under that responsibility.

I feel that being a professional goes beyond what you learn in school. I believe that you have to be determined to continuously learn new topics and stimulate the mind whether that is scientific knowledge or new technologies.

It is my determination to strive to become a dentist in which is profession not just in terms of manual skills but also in terms of knowledge and wisdom. I hope to become a professional in which many patients can relate to and rely on by being competent and able to self assess myself.

To become an adequate professional, many skills must be acquired. One of the main skills is to learn how to communicate with the patient in the most efficient way to fully understand what the patients problem is in order to help them in the most effective manner. It is also important to express empathy towards the patient so they feel comfortable in the environment and so they can gain trust in their healthcare provider. A professional should maintain respect for their patients and hold themselves with integrity.

The key elements I would like to learn from dental school is to be a competent and compassionate professional. I would like to build skills that enable me to learn from my peers and build networks. I also want to constantly keep up with the new advances made in the field so I can build the habit of becoming a life long learner. These skills will hopefully enable me to be a proficient healthcare professional involved in making a positive difference in my community.

Ethics is what an honest practice is run on. Many might be afraid of making mistakes in practice, but it is conquering the fear and fixing a mistake is what differentiates a quality dentist. Errors in procedures are very common, yet very few practitioners will be ethical enough to correct their mistakes for the sake of honesty.

I hope to become a polished professional and a compassionate dentist. My mission will be to lead an ethical practice where all patients are treated equally. I hope to partner up with other health care providers and work as a team to achieve maximal results for the patient. My patient's well being will be my primary concern.

It is very critical to not forget that the art of dentistry is not key to success as a dentist. Professionalism is what allows the patient to develop a healthy relationship with the dentist and build trust in the caregiver.

Professionalism is a defining trait in quality care. One can be a great dentist, yet if there is a lack of professionalism in his/her manners, patients will be very hesitant in attending appointments, and eventually might seek other venues of treatment. It is very important to present yourself in a manner that represents a professional and run a practice that will live up to such standards.

Ethics and professionalism are very important subjects to master while attending dental school. I have come to an understanding this week of that they are key components in becoming a dentist and even more critical when running one's own practice.

I intend to use every resource offered by NYUCD to become a gentle and thorough Dentist. I hope to learn how to deliver the best care in the most efficient of manners, while offering maximal consideration and sensitivity to the patients. My mission will be to provide comprehensive dental care leaving my patients with beautiful and healthy smiles.

I think what I want to achieve is to develop a solid understanding of foundational knowledge, and to hone my clinical skills so that professionally I can be a competent practitioner. In addition, I want to develop personal qualities to be a better communicator, better presenter, be more empathetic with the needs of patients. To be a competent manager or employer to my employees and a trusting colleague my peers can lean on. Furthermore, I want to learn the latest development in the field of dentistry to stay up to date with the frontier in dental research, and hopefully to spearhead research in dentistry in the future.

I think becoming a professional means maintaining a character of high standard not only in your professional career, but in every aspect of one's life. One must put the well being of the patient above anything else. This includes possessing a solid understanding of foundational scientific knowledge and clinical skills to carry out safe and comfortable treatment plan. Also the possession of good communication skills, presentation skills and the humbleness to be able to receive feedbacks from co workers. This allows the success of team management, which is important for the well being of the patient. Moreover, one needs to be empathetic, allowing understanding and trust to be established between the doctor and patient, as well as the doctor and other professionals. Lastly, professionalism is a standard of conduct that one sets upon himself to always monitor his or her own progress throughout their career and other areas of their lives. It is in essence, a heightened sense of self awareness that allows one to always strive for higher standard in life.
