As a dentist, I hope to be someone who is a life-long learner by staying up-do-date with the latest discoveries in oral health. , I hope to learn more about the molecular mechanisms of oral diseases, and how these findings can be applied in a clinical setting. Working with world renowned researchers on a variety of research topics at NYUCD will give me the opportunity to learn and be part of the forefront of advancements in oral health.

As a practicing dentist in the future, I hope to continue to give back to the global and local community. Most importantly, helping the marginalized, educating others about preventative oral health and staying up-to-date with current research are all aspects I hope to incorporate in my practice, in order to provide the highest standard of care to my patients. I hope to actively participate through the various outreach programs offered by this department. In doing so, my goal is to learn from other visionaries within the department and gain a greater sense of civic duty. The international externship program is also something I find attractive about NYUCD. Educating and empowering the needy about oral health all over the world will not only allow me to expand my perspective of oral health and delivery in different cultures, but also reinstate the idea of giving back to the less fortunate.

In order to become a professional, at the basic level, one must obtain an education and develop a skill set in a specialized area to be able to practice with expertise. In order to practice with professionalism one must employ integrity, competency, and academic/skilled excellence in that specialized area. It is also crucial for the individual to keep current with research such that they can provide patients with current treatment/therapy using evidence-based practice. Furthermore, professionals are bound by professional codes, professional standards of practice, and ethical regulations (pertaining to both the public and the patient/public) that thy must adhere to.

I am committed to practicing with compassion and integrity. Throughout my education, I aspire to achieve academic and clinical excellence such that I can provide comprehensive patient-centered care. Throughout my education and professional career, I plan to participate in local and global outreach programs to provide dental care for the underserved.

In my path towards becoming a healthcare professional, I hope to first gain a solid foundation in the sciences. This will provide me with the background knowledge that I need to become a successful dental practitioner. Subsequently, I hope to acquire the clinical skills needed to perform excellent dental work. I also intend to learn to effectively communicate and work in tandem with those around me in order to do what is best for each patient. If I am uncertain of something, I intend to exhaust my resources to find a solution. Finally, I plan to uphold a high standard of ethical and moral character in making everyday decisions.

Although we are being judged based upon achieving various competencies, I aspire to become a proficient dental professional. The word 'proficient' means being able to perform something repetitively while maintaining the same high quality of work. I intend to reach this goal through practice and dedication for the sake of myself and for the sake of those around me. As a dentist, I will be responsible for the healthcare needs of the community and I am determined to become the best dental professional that I can possibly be. My time at NYUCD marks the start of this journey.

To me, the most important part is honest, open communication. If you make a mistake, be honest and admit your wrong doings. If you witness others doing something they shouldn't, give them the chance to admit their mistake, and give them a second chance to do better next time. If you are unsure of something or are not competent, know your limits.

Personal goals: do community outreach, see other communities in d3/d4, do the best I can academically, smile and be upbeat and positive! This is my lifelong goal, and even when I go through struggles, I should step back and realize that I have worked hard to have the opportunity to go through these struggles!

I want to improve my approachability. To do this, I will smile more, be an up-beat, positive person, and help others. I realize there will probably be difficult times in dental school, and others will go through struggles as well. I want to be there for them.

Becoming a professional requires developing many skills. It is important to use empathy when communicating with patients. Being compassionate and understanding will make it so the patient will feel comfortable and will return for care in the future. It is important to understand what the patient wants and educate them about what will be best for them, while keeping in mind thatthe goal is to make them happy and keep them healthy, merging what they want vs. what they need.

I hope to use open, honest communication to create a positive professional environment. To me, a positive professional environment is one in which peers can work cohesively as a team with a common goal in mind - to provide the best possible comprehensive care for individuals.

I will strive to be a compassionate professional who cares about each and every patient. I want to be more than competent; I want to be proficient, both in procedure and in patient interaction so I can develop meaningful patient relationships. I want to be a lifelong learner who provides the best possible care and who stays current in the field with research and technology. I want to be a positive influence within the community.

Becoming a dentist takes a lot of hard work and dedication.However, having the title DDS is not everything. It is important to always practice with honesty and integrity. Without integrity, there is no meaning to what you are doing. Patients trust us as professionals to do the right thing and it is our job to live up to that expectation.

As a dental student at NYUCD I would like to graduate as a competent dentist that is responsible, caring, and able to provide patients with the best dental care possible. During my time here, I hope to hone my clinical skills. Additionally, I would like to participate in community outreach programs.

I have come to understand that becoming a professional carries with it certain responsibilities and obligations both to the community and the profession. These include ethical practice, service to the community, and upholding the standards of the profession.

My personal mission as I progress through these next fours years of dental school is to 1) Attain the knowledge and skills required to be able to provide the best possible care to the community I will serve after leaving school. 2) I hope to further develop my understanding in the area of research in the hope that I can uncover new insights which may enhance the profession. 3) I hope to proceed in all my endeavors according to the high ethical standards rightly demanded by the profession.

Through my time here at NYUCD, I hope to acquire skills and knowledge that will make me a competent and successful dentist. I hope to grow not only academically but also on a personal level. I look forward to many new experiences, developing new relationships and learning from my peers as well as faculty.

Having good ethics is really important in Dentistry. To me deciding what is right and wrong has always been intuitive to me. What is best for the patient is what always comes first. Throughout dental school I will come across situations where my ethics will be tested in the clinic and that will only make me become a better dentist so I will know for the future.

I feel dentistry is a profession that allows me to accomplish another goal in life as in starting a family and being able to provide for them as well as myself. It will also satisfy me professionally by opening my own practice and creating long lasting patient bonds.

Becoming a professional is probably the scariest step in my life that I will take. The main responsibility is on me. I also feel the responsibility to educate others. The patients will look up to me for guidance and I don't want to fail them.

Becoming a professional I believe is the biggest step one can take. It is when you take all the knowledge and skills you have acquired and use it to benefit the community. All the responsibility now lies in your hands.

To me it is the duty of the professional to keep current in their field of practice. Especially dentistry that is constantly evolving it is really important to continue education programs and stay on top of innovative treatments. This way the doctor can best treat their patient. It is important to me to evolve with dentistry throughout my career.

In my four years here at NYUCD I will gain the knowledge and ability to best serve my patients and the community. I will do this by mastering the basic sciences, become proficient in the lab and clinic, and participate in community and global outreach programs, while always keeping the patients needs first with the highest integrity.

Everyone has done unethical behavior at least once.  In terms of education, unethical behavior would be cheating, not helping students who is in need. The important lesson I learned from my previous unethical behavior is that it holds you back. Besides feeling guilty, there is no self-improvement.  Since we will become health professionals, these unethical behaviors can jeopardize our future patients' health.  More importantly, you will find yourself standing at the same spot when others are moving forward to achieve their goals.

I want to become a dentist that patients can trust after graduating from NYU dental school.  I am a Korean American, and there are many Korean dentists working in New York, and New Jersey area.  I also have working experience with few Korean dentists.  But they all to limit their practice to Korean patients.  I want to be a dentist who can earn the trust from all kinds of patients regardless of ethnicity, religions, and nationality.  In order to do that, I think that communication with patients is very important.  But, it is the area that I am weakest at.  Beside the knowledge and clinical skills, I want to improve my ability to communicate with patients and peers.

Becoming a professional requires many abilities such as ability to self-assess, clinical skills, knowledge, and responsibility.  One thing that is not easy to do the self-assessment because people usually rationalize themselves to feel less responsible.  I have rationalized myself in the past, and I may still doing it without noticing.  It is evident that self-assessment skill is critical in order to improve myself.  Therefore, I want to improve my ability to self-assess to become true professional.

Becoming a professional requires responsibility.  In terms of health professions, we use our knowledge and skills to treat people's health.  If these knowledge and skills are wrongfully used, it can cause harm to people even death.  I believe it is why health professional schools require extensive studying and strict discipline to minimize the unfortunate outcome.
We currently are at the starting line for professional progress.  By gaining scientific knowledge, clinical skill, communication skill and ethics, we will take one step forward.

After graduating from NYU dental school, I want to be a dentist that patients can trust.  I want to earn the trust from patients by showing my confidence in my clinical skills and knowledge. I wish to achieve the best clinical skill and knowledge from NYU dental school.

I am excited to become a health professional so that I can use my knowledge and specific skill set to help people in need. I find it personally fulfilling to follow in my grandfather's and father's footsteps down this path. This will be an incredible experience of personal growth.

I want my time at NYUCD to challenge me academically, personally, and professionally. I hope to come away from this program as a competent dentist with excellent communication and clinical skills. I also wish to make lasting relationships with my peers and faculty.

You don’t become a professional overnight. I think I’ve made it this far and have learned from a lot of my experiences in my education and my work. I think becoming a better person or just enriching the being we are will in turn make us better professionals.

I hope to become a competent dentist who is knowledgeable and skillful about this field. I want to be able to give back to others whether it is in NY or around the globe. I hope to join an outreach and gain more confidence in treating various patients and learn more about the different cultures we get to help. I believe my philosophy of dentistry will continue to grow as I continue my dental education career at NYUCD.

As a dental profession, I hope to always conduct myself in a way that displays maturity. My goal is to keep my patients as a priority and maintain meaningful relationships with colleagues in healthcare field. It is really important to me to have a healthy balance between my personal life and professional career.

I would like to strive to provide the best care possible for my patients while upholding a code of ethical conduct and following legal regulations. In addition, when treating patients of different cultures and ethnic backgrounds I will try to learn from and respect these different cultures while providing care.

My ultimate goal is to provide the best care possible for my patients. To accomplish that goal I will need to be clinically competent and be able to communicate clearly with co-workers, my patients, and other professionals in the field. I also think it is important to continue my education in dentistry after dental school and to establish a professional network with other dentists. I have not decided yet wether I will specialize in any particular field of dentistry. As I progress through dental school perhaps there will be a certain field of dentistry I will want to pursue further after dental school.

Becoming a professional involves communicating and collaborating with other professionals in the field and the desire to improve one's self through self assessment and constructive criticism provided by peers.

Becoming a professional involves communicating and collaborating with other professionals in the field and the desire to improve one's self through self assessment and constructive criticism provided by peers.

Self assessment and peer assessment are great ways to track one's progress as a professional. Self and peer assessment give professionals an idea of which areas they need improvement on to become the best health care provider they can be.

My ultimate goal is to provide the best care possible for my patients. To accomplish that goal I will need to be clinically competent and be able to communicate clearly with co-workers, my patients, and other professionals in the field. I also think it is important to continue my education in dentistry after dental school and to establish a professional network with other dentists.

I feel that we should treat people with the utmost care and honor in every situation that we can. Patients are trusting us with their health and even their lives. They deserve the best for believing in us.

I want to grow to become a person that can be with any and all people. My life's goal is to become worldly, but still have a sense of self, truth and clarity. My relationship with God, family and those who cross my path should be a clear reflection of my character which can be seen, accepted and respected by all who I meet.

I can't believe that I am actually starting my career. It feels like I have always been dreaming about and waiting for this point in my life, and now it is finally here. I'm excited about actually being able to start building my dream. I felt a bit nervous that I wouldn't be able to handle it but there are plenty of people before me who were able to do it.
Becoming a professional means a lot to me. This is a step in the direction that I want to take that will push me toward making my community a better place
I am excited to see what is to come in the future. I am beginning to see how important it is to protect vital patient information and uphold a certain demeanor that reflects the profession.

To positively affect the world by promoting change and working to make each moment I experience the best that it can be. These experiences encompass my relationship with God, my family and my peers. I want to serve as a person who can express his feelings and effectively listen and understand.
I want my experience at NYUCD to help me grow into an excellent clinician who is proficient and provides the best care for each patient. Not best in comparison to other dentists, but best for the patient as an individual.
My goal is to serve my community, both locally and globally. I plan to help provide care and serve the underserved.

As a professional I will need to become confident in my technical and didactic abilities. Not only will I need to apply these skills, but also skills in communication, understanding, and business management. I hope to join my community and be a positive addition by providing overall excellent care, as well as volunteering and educating.

My Mission: To become a compatent, sensitive, and successful Dental Professional. To be a respected, trusted, and a loyal colleague to my peers and mentors. To build standards of respect, ethics, compassion, and acceptance through curriculum and by developing relationships with the diverse student body, faculty, and patients. To develop exceptional technical and communication skills by accessing the resources provided to me and not limited to: clinical experience, shadowing students in rotation and specialties, and participating in outreach programs. To enjoy my journey here while never swaying from my mission.

Through the years at NYU, I strive to evolve my love for dentistry into a passion and find confirmation that I have selected the right path to follow. Through the rounds of each specialty that I will make at NYU, I want to find which career that will not only make me happy, but also continuously challenge me in the years to come. I want to receive the proper amount of education and instruction in order to feel comfortable in my skill set to perform dentistry confidently. I hope to make friendships that will stick through the years that can be used in our future professions.

I want to own a practice with integrity, one known for its commitment to giving patients the best care possible in the most ethical means. I want to be able to start an organization that gives access to dental care to areas and populations not just on occasion- but continually. I want to be able to lead this organization and my career with grace, kindness and resourcefulness.

I want to learn how to become the kind of proficient, independent, successful dentist that makes solid contributions to society- not only on a professional basis in encounters with colleagues and patients but also on a larger scale so that the good that I do paves a path for others to follow suit.

To become a competent professional, I look to obtain extensive knowledge in the field of dentistry through both coursework and clinical practice. Great communication skills is one of the most important attributes to have, as I would need to be respectful, culturally aware and communicate in such a way that I earn their trust. I want to gain experience in both communicating with patients and technique skills. Most of all, be to an excellent profession, I want to be passionate on what I do and I want to show patients and other healthcare professionals my passion towards my career. It will earn trust and leave a good impression to those around me.

Through this peer assessment aspect of the course, I have become more aware on how I carry myself as a professional. In society, we are constantly judged, main on our appearance and how we talk to others. By implementing this, we are being motivated to carry ourselves as a professional dentist on day 1, despite ever picking up a dental instrument. From looking at the syllabus, I like how the curriculum incorporates a hand-full of courses that strives us to be professionals, instead of having only courses that focuses on science- and dentistry-related. I feel that this will prove beneficial when we actually have to interact and communicate with patients, where their assessment means a lot.

My mission is to a professional competent Dentist. I want to treat patients with the best patient-centered care by efficiently communicating with my patients, as well as my oral health care team. In addition, I want a strong network with fellow Dentists and other healthcare professionals (Doctors and nurses), so that I have unlimited resources to go to. As a healthcare professional, I want to be a good advocate towards oral health by participating in community programs. Lastly, as a student in a difficult program, I want to have a balanced lifestyle, such as making time for friends and having time to relax.
My mission through my four years at dental school is to become a competent dentist trained to confidently deal with any situation presented to me with skill, compassion, honesty, and enthusiasm.

Being a professional not only consists of being competent and skillful at your profession, but most importantly behaving in an ethical way. This also includes being honest as well as responsible. You must always put put your patient first.
To matriculate and mature as a student into a competent professional who one day can use his skills to help and teach those most in need eg. those living in third world countries.

As a professional, I must maintain a high standard both in the clinic as well as in my every day life. The community and public will assess me constantly and I am expected to behave in a way that exceed the standard.

My mission statement to grow up into a technical as well as sociable dentist which my patient trusts and relies upon. I also want to not only become a competent dentist after graduation, but also get involved in the community services and give back to the underserved populations during and after school.
When a patient comes in with pain and no money, what should I do?
I want to explore different specialty programs to find the one that I have passion for.
I still need to work on communication skills. Also I hope to find out my strength and weakness through this self-assessment program so then I can improve my weaknesses.
I feel like I am at ground zero now and hope to reach my goal at the end of four years.

My goal is to become a competent dental professional that strives to provide excellent patient care and an advocate that promotes preventive care and importance of oral health. I want to serve and to educate underserved communities by participating in local or global outreach programs, and I hope to make a difference in our community.
I will learn more through the classes and from talking to my peers in order to be competent in ethics

I would like to build good networks and gain enough experience in serving the public as well as gain good experience of public policies. I will use the knowledges I learned and go back to China and helping develop the Chinese dental cares.
I will try to learn more to do networking, which is my weak point. I will join student clubs and improve my interpersonal skills.
I feel comfortable of talking to people in a proper way. And I will try to learn as much as I could in order to be a competent professional
I am just entering the school and I will try to gain experience as soon as possible in order to be more professional
My mission statement is to develop my personal skills in not only dental experience and competency, and also in interpersonal skills like networkings and communication.

If I stayed true to myself, then I will stay true to my patients, colleagues, and the faculty. Finding leeway might get me out of trouble temporarily, but in a long run, it won't do me any good to better myself.

For next 4 years at NYUCD, I will acquire knowledge and a skill set to competently treat my patients and provide comprehensive care.  I will learn how to effectively communicate with my patients and other health professionals. I will learn how to present myself professionally and understand my duties as a dental professional.  I will learn how to juggle between my professional and personal life, and I will always be ready and focused when I see my patients.  I will explore my career options as a dentist and find a direction by the time of graduation.

Being a professional is being competent at a certain job, that requires education and experience to do it right.  Passion is a key to being a professional, especially in the field of dentistry where new technology pops up everyday to improve quality of service dentist provide.
I am starting D1, gaining basic scientific knowledge and getting a vague idea about how to apply it to real patients in the future.
I will always try to relate to my future patients with understanding, honesty, professionalism; I will support them on their way to health and well being.

I know there will be great challenges that will require hard work and a lot of time. I just hope i will have enough time to do all that is required and be able to spend time with my daughter. I will do my best, I will work hard to graduate and become a confident professional; i want to set a good example for my daughter, i want her to understand that nothing comes easy, that only with hard work, honesty you can achieve your goals.

I am on the road to become a dental professional which involves many challenges that include adjusting to a new lifestyle that is always evolving, keeping up with innovations and technology etc.  It is a way of life and an inlet of education that is constantly changing.

Some people say that good things and luck happen to those who wait; however, I found out that is not true. Good things happen to those who work hard, who want to be better, who aim for perfection,  and who love what they do, who never hold on to bad things, who never give up, who hope, and who always try to help those in need.
I want to be able to achieve confidence, professionalism, and excellent manual dexterity that will allow me to be a successful dentist and open doors to specialization.

By being accepted to NYUCD I am one step closer to my main goal, which is to become a dental professional; I know there is a challenging and hard road in front of me, but I know that I will overcome every rock on my way because I believe in honesty, hard work, and empathy towards this profession.

Throughout our dental careers we will encounter several situations where our moral judgment will be put to the test. Its important to have a strong moral compass and stay true to what you believe irrespective of how you may be viewed in the eyes of your peers. I believe its important to ask for guidance along the way and to know your limitations as health care provider.

A professional to me is someone who conducts themselves in a manner that exemplifies the dental profession to the fullest. It's important as a professional to develop great team management, communication and teamwork skills. Becoming a dental professional is a journey that will take some time and hard work but it is one that I look forward to embarking upon.

I vow to use the experience, knowledge, and expertise I gain over the next four years to strive to be the best friend, father and dental professional I can be. Getting involved in several clubs and activities throughout my duration at NYUCD will allow me to build character and relationships that I aim to keep for countless years post graduation.

My mission throughout the 4 years of dental school is to become a confident individual who is able to not only practice but also have the knowledge to educate and share it with others, and also build communication skills that will allow me to help the patients be comfortable
I will do the best of my abilities to master the teachings I receive here at NYUCD to become a competent dentist, leader in society, and a caring and social person.

My goal for my next 4 years is to learn how to become a competent dentist by enhancing skills in communication, knowledge and hands-on skills. Also, to help underserved populations and learn what it's like to be the one who help, and extend the experience post-graduation.

As part of the NYUCD Class of 2017, I plan on expanding my horizons, contributing to the community, meeting new people, and making life long connections. As I enter NYUCD as a student, I will be learning and experiencing many new things, and look forward to leaving as a changed person; a professional.

To become a professional dentist, I will keep my passion on dental field. From the school, I will learn everything I can to be competent dentist academically and clinically. For first and second year, I will focus on academic knowledge while I will enhance my hand skills from simulation lab. Once I get confident on knowledge with skills it will make easier to treat patients end of second year. Throughout years, I will behave as professional all the time, be respectful during communication, and understand different cultures.

My goal through NYU College of Dentistry is to be competent dental profession who can be respected and trusted by colleague, professors, and patients. Not only being confident dentist, I want to gather dental health care information as much I can and I want to make a informative website in different languages to keep people healthy. From professors, I want to learn how to manage dental clinic while developing excellent bonding with patients and team members.

My mission is to gain academic and technical confidence throughout my four years at this university. I will strive to take full advantage of the diverse patient base this school has to offer and will do my best to establish and maintain strong relationships with my classmates, mentors and advisors. I will try my best to keep myself on track and will approach my studies with hard work, passion and dedication.

Here's the deal, all I care about in life is getting through the next 4 years of dental school.  Yes, I want to grow to be more professional, and yes, I want to make friends and be successful.  But what I want more than anything is simply to make it through the program.  I have always had poor study habits and I get stressed out easily, so I need to make sure I can manage my time and emotions effectively.  I just want to prove that I am capable of doing this, that I have what it takes to make it through these 4 grueling years.  If, in 4 years, I have made it to the other side and can call myself a DDS, then I will have done everything I've sought out to accomplish.

Seriously, though, even this statement is too casual.  I need to start acting like an adult.  I have too much fun with life, and though that is crucial, I need to be able to hide some of that vigor from patients.  I need to be calm and speak softly but with authority, rather than running around yelling and making a spectacle of myself.  It is time to really grow up.

Becoming a professional is more than simply being proficient in your career path, it is a way of behaving that elevates you in the public's eye.  A professional is required to be ethical, relatable, knowledgable, and to behave in a prudent and respectable manner.  Personally, I think I have everything down, except for the behavior aspects.  It's not to say that I behave badly, but rather that I believe I am too casual with others.  I think I speak too loudly and am too blunt and forward.  To me, learning how to speak properly to patients and colleagues will be my primary objective; hopefully as I grow in decorum I will strengthen all of the other aspects of professionalism that I feel I already have.

In my time at NYU, I will strive to become a clinician worthy of serving in the US Navy.  I hope to establish and maintain close relationships with my peers.  I will focus on ethics in order to practice with integrity.  I will develop my communication skills in order to effectively and charismatically interact with my patients.  I will use my skills to aid in humanitarian efforts.  I will become a contributing member of my community, and I will assist in providing care to those areas with limited access.  After serving my time in the Navy, I will consider exploring avenues in academia, possibly in both research and education.
To also supplement my education with research opportunities and have the opportunity to continue and specialize in orthodontistry.

To become a competent and confident practitioner and earn the respect and trust of my mentors and colleagues. To gain experiences via global and local outreach and to strengthen my ability reassure, communicate, and empathize with patients under my care.

While working hard to be a sound and competent professional I hope to gain the experience and knowledge necessary for me to develop and maintain a strong and ever growing business. A business that is focused on providing the highest level of patient care.

I wish to work hard to become the best dentist I can be; and in the process develop strong personal relationships, strong clinical abilities, a deeper passion for volunteer work and improve everyday as a professional.

To me, becoming a professional means feeling competent in your practice, exhibiting excellent knowledge and skill, while treating your patients and colleagues in an appropriate and respectful manner. It is also about representing your profession in the most positive light and constantly striving to learn more and perfect your skill.

I hope to obtain and retain a wide set of skills, experiences and competencies that will lead to my ultimate success as a healthcare professional and as a person.  The education itself is my main priority and perfecting my manual dexterity, technical skills, and expanding my scientific and clinical knowledge are all essential for attaining and deserving this DDS degree. NYU will instill confidence and a sense of responsibility in me as it shapes me into the professional that I know I will become. I hope to perfect my interpersonal skills with patients and fellow clinicians in order to gain their trust and respect. Global and local outreach are very important to me, and I plan on becoming very involved in these community service opportunities. This will also provide me with exposure to various cultures, religions and ways of life, which will mold me into a well-rounded and knowledgeable practitioner. This will allow me to connect and relate with my patients and colleagues. NYUCD focuses highly on ethics and morals, and I hope this will further motivate me to improve upon my comprehensive moral code.

Unfortunately I've herd many stories of dentists acting unethically to make more money, however I also personally know more dentists who are strictly against any such thing.  Ethics of dentistry requires one to put on the shoes of patient, and ask if this is morally acceptable or not, and I aim to be an ethical and respectable dentist who provides the best care to his patients.

I want to learn to be a skilled dentist that can support society and become a leader in my community, in order to educate the importance of oral hygiene to the rest of my community and to serve those who are underserved in my community.

I think becoming a professional requires one to change their perspective of how one views their self.  Rather from viewing yourself from the inside, being a professional requires the ability to look from the outside in, realizing how certain actions or words would cause you to be perceived a certain way.

Rather from viewing yourself from the inside, being a professional requires the ability to look from the outside in, realizing how certain actions or words would cause you to be perceived a certain way

Throughout this semester, I think I have been able to be more cognizant of what a professional should look like and internalized not only image but the character of a professional and hopefully I will be able to apply these learned and perspectives.

I want to learn to be a proficient and independent dentist that contributes to society as a whole, not just in the education of oral hygiene, but the overall education of community and overall health.

I want to become the type of dentist that does not only clinical work but is an advocate for progression in the community, no matter where I am.  My ultimate goal is to travel the world and the rest of United States and work in underserved areas.  I'd like to be able to build up communities and create environments that are health conscious and geared towards learning and improving. Eventually I'd like to be able to do a bit of everything; orthodontics, periodontics, aesthetics, pediatrics, the entire dental spectrum.  

For now though, the goal is to work on becoming a better student, work on communication skills, do well in classes, and enjoy the start of the learning process that I hope will never end.

A professional is someone knowledgeable in his field and has the ability to apply this knowledge in practice. It is important to be respectful and mindful to others and know how to work well in a team. Professionals should be able to make ethical decisions and weigh out all possibilities  after proper research. There should always be constant growth either through self evaluation or from other's criticism. Professionalism also carries on outside of work and a person's role in society. We should be leaders in the community and reach out to those in need..

My goal is to become a competent, well rounded, and educated dentist who can make ethical and unbiased decisions to enhance a patient's oral health. Dentistry involves more than just fixing teeth. It affect's a patient's overall facial appearance, emotional, and physical well being. I hope to accomplish this as a dental professional by promoting oral hygiene, screening for diseases, improving dental function, and aesthetics.

I plan to be extremely ethical in treating my future patients.  This is done by being conservative with my treatment.  I have seen dentists consistently over treat their patients and I vow not to fall into the same category.  Also, I plan on putting the patient first rather than be more business minded.

After a week in dental school, I must say that the task of becoming a dentist will be extremely hard, but extremely rewarding.  I know that in my heart.  I think I will have to re-strategize how I budget my time.

I wonder how being a professional will change they way I think.  This is interesting because we are so used to thinking about ourselves 24/7.  When a person's health is in our hands, we have to think about them first.  I hope to live up to this standard.

On the road to becoming a professional, there is a great deal of responsibility that comes with the territory.  Does this scare me?  No, it does not.  This motivates me to do better each and every day.  Being a professional is like being challenged each moment of your life because other people hold you to a higher standard.  In order to do your duty to society, you have to live up to their standards.

As of now, in terms of ethics,  Dr. More has been teaching us about being ethical.  We discussed case presentations, which were more or less based on cheating.  I think cheating is so unprofessional that people should be kicked out for it.  This is a professional school graduating dentists who will treat patients in the outside world.  What good are they going to do if they cheat their patients too?

Because there is such a shortage of dentists in my neighborhood, I want to make a difference in my community by attending dental school.  By learning how to be a professional, I can give back to the community by treating and educating members of my community to live healthier lives.

My goal is to become a professional, compassionate, knowledgeable and responsible dentist to my patients after my four years of studies at NYUCD.  I expect to encounter tremendous hardships and challenges in this journey, which I am determined to overcome by studying hard together with my peer students.  I hope to become a better person, whose profession can make a little change in others’ lives, by starting my practice, participating in the community services and outreach programs to care for the underserved.

I will show ethical behavior in both a didactic and clinical setting. I will always be ethical toward patients in the clinic but I have a hard time dealing when patients refuse treatment when they need it because of religious or other beliefs. I especially have a hard time understanding and dealing when parents make decisions against having dental procedures done for their children that would improve their oral health and overall health.

I am strongly considering pursing oral surgery after dental school. I find the field fascinating and I would very much want to know more about it. I remember watching my first surgical extraction, which I found it to be amazing! I want to know more details of how doctors of dental surgery become oral surgeons and about the profession itself and what it entails. I want to know while I am here at NYUCD what I need to do to ensure that when I decide to pursue oral surgery I will have the necessary grades, and skills to be able to apply and attain a spot as a post-graduate student.

I need to make sure I do not fall behind studying or lose my focus because that will greatly affect my grades and my path to become a profession. I definitely need to be more approachable to my peers by introducing myself to more people and keeping in contact with the people I meet.

I believe that I would be a competent doctor of dental surgery after I graduate from NYUCD. I will go above and beyond to help patients. I believe I need to work on my communication skills so when I explain procedures or post-operative instructions to patients they will understand and be able to perform the post-operative care at home. I need to be able to be approachable so patients will not fear asking questions and then not getting the correct care they deserve.

I have had prior experiences working in dental practices and in a dental insurance company. I believe that my experiences will help me effectively communicate with patients to have them understand what treatment options are available, what is covered under their insurance, if and  what payment plans are available and develop a plan of action by prioritizing procedures and deciding what needs to be done first and organizing procedures and appointments so the patient receives the best care in the least amount of time she or he will have to spend in the clinic.

My goal for dental school is to graduate a competent doctor of dental surgery. At the end of my education at NYUCD I want to have the skills necessary so that patients will trust my diagnostic and treating abilities. I believe I am a very compassionate person and will go above and beyond to help my patients and make them feel comfortable under my care. I think it is important for me to be happy in my profession which is why I choose dentistry. I can picture myself every day of the week waking up happy going to work happy and leaving the practice tired, but happy. Also I choose dentistry because I will be able to earn a salary to support a family. Dentists must exhibit a high standard of morals and ethics because the public entrusts them with their health care needs. Sometimes, ethics can mean working in a place that is in a sort of gray area that is neither black nor white. This requires one to cultivate a state of mind that provides good judgment, balance, and equilibrium between right and wrong, right and more right, and sometimes the lesser of two evils. The goal of being ethically aware is to act accordingly and appropriately.

The most obvious example of ethics in dentistry is to know when to refer out because of one's limitations and weaknesses in doing certain procedures. This is a balance act since ego can sometimes delude one to have a false sense of confidence, which could further result with clinical disasters and possible law suits. On the other hand, practicing dentistry means to venture slightly out of one's comfort zone in order to grow clinically and to become a better dentist. While the risks and rewards of practicing dentistry must be assessed, it is important to keep the patient's best interest as a top priority.

Once admitted into dental school at NYUCD, I felt blessed that my dreams of becoming a dentist would soon initiate. It was then that I made a promise to God that I will devote my studies to Him as a form of worship and incorporate my faith to motivate me in my studies. The challenges that lie ahead will require me to grow spiritually, as well as to mature personally as a man of compassion. I believe the New York experience will allow me to improve my interpersonal skills and to learn how to work with my colleagues, professors, and future patients.

I have also made it my personal goal to be involved in school activities as much as possible. I will strive to promote community spirit as I partake in clubs and study groups.

In order to participate in outreach programs in Latin America, I also wish to learn Spanish on my own accord. This will facilitate my ability to communicate with Spanish speaking patients in the clinic, as well as in my own future practice. Everyday, I will learn a minimum of 10 dental related vocabulary terms.

One thing that I would like to improve on is my conversational skills in the professional setting. I am inspired by those before me who have gotten through dental school and have succeeded in transforming themselves from socially awkward to conversational superstars. This is especially important in cultivating trust with colleagues and patients. Carrying myself as I normally would as a rowdy, thug-like, manly man does not fly in the professional setting. So I must reinvent myself to become a sophisticated man of class while remembering not to be too uptight and stuck up. Although I am truly proud of my academic achievements and admissions into dental school, I must remain humble and remember that I am blessed to have the opportunity to grow in the city of New York. NYC is the greatest city in the world where anyone who is anyone has presumably passed through on their way to finding professional success.

Becoming a professional is a multifaceted topic that requires much experience, wisdom, insight, and hard work. It requires many skill sets such as interpersonal skills, the ability to work in teams, and the willingness to admit to oneself that they are only one individual in a network of many. One must also be perceived as knowledgable, compassionate, and personable, and have a working knowledge of politics and business.
            
            I ultimately feel that my heart is in the right place and that my motivation for becoming a doctor is genuine. However, the skill sets required to mature professionally warrants me to learn how to speak intelligibly in public settings and to be sensitive of different cultures and value systems. To this end, I look forward to working with everyone in the diverse student body of NYUCD and to be exposed to people from all sorts of cultural and academic backgrounds.

On a 1 to 10 scale, 10 being the highest, I rate myself professionally at a 5. My score reflects my 6 years of work experience in the automotive industry professionally interfacing with service writers, technicians, sales associates, and customers. This required me to communicate technical information to those who might not have had a good understanding of  mechanical principles. My skills are transferable because in dentistry, I will also have to educate patients about their comprehensive treatment needs and communicate scientific knowledge to them in a way they can understand fully.

I will aspire to grow competent in all things dentistry and to mature accordingly as a health care professional. Towards the goal of skilled proficiency, I will develop my confidence in performing successful procedures and strive to meet all of my patients' expectations by managing their comprehensive treatment needs with evidence based knowledge. An unbiased assessment of my strengths, weaknesses, and limitations will be needed to learn to work in teams and to collaborate with other health care professionals.
                  
                  My other goals in dental school are to be involved in research and to use my mechanical engineering background to advance the future of dentistry. I will use my ability to critically think and solve problems as well as my knowledge of conceptual physics and technology to realize unmatched achievements in areas of functional smile design. I am interested in exploring the uses of CAD/CAM technology in prosthodontics, immediate load implants, oral surgery, and esthetic design.
                  
                  Lastly, I will develop my character as a man of humility and genuine compassion. To this end, I will need to evaluate my passions seriously with respect to altruistic outreaches and community involvement.

As a health professional in the dental field, one must be technically skilled to the highest point of one's ability.

Over the next four years and the extension of my dental career, I will continuously seek ways to improve myself as a competent dentist. I will always will put the welfare of my patients as my number one priority by; displaying empathy, being throughly efficient and effective in my procedures and being up to date with evidence-based cases. I would also like to extend this relationship past my patients and into the dental field. I would like to gain to the uttermost respect of my colleagues.

Within 4 years of dental school, what I would like to achieve is to obtain a DDS degree which would open up more opportunities such as proceeding onto becoming a specialist. In addition, I would like to build a professional social network: a group of professionals that I can turn into.

When I enter the dental field I want my patients to have faith in my skills and abilities, knowing that whatever procedure is necessary will be done with care and precision.  In order for this to occur, I need to develop a vast knowledge of dental sciences as well as hone my clinical skills.   However, this alone with not make me the dentist I want to become.  I look forward to  building personal relationships with my  patients here at NYUCD, so that I learn how to establish the trust needed for consistent oral healthcare.

I want to be the sharp dentist who possesses strong academic foundation and facilitates the most accurate and best treatment to each patient through macroscopic thinking process and hearty care. Furthermore, I want to focus on MPH program as well as DDS program because prevention is the best treatment. Therefore, I want to pursue to be the professor at dental school as well to help out people who are underrepresented.

In U.S., many patients with financial burden lack the proper access to dental care and this is very unfortunate. I hope to participate in many outreach programs to help out these patients with the skills that I learn from NYUCD.

My goal in dental school is to know each and everyone in the group practice on a personal level and to continue our relationship past professional school. I would like to learn how to communicate with patients effectively prescribing the treatment best for them.

The mission of dental school is to provide exceptional health care to communities lacking health care, while communicating with patients effectively so they can get the proper oral health care that they deserve.

I want to set my expectations high, accomplish the goals that I set for myself and achieve even further beyond that, and graduate as a competent practitioner prepared with the skill set I need to impress my colleagues and face the challenges that come next. I also want to remain focused throughout dental school, especially during my first and second years, and not loose sight of why I came here in the first place.  I am here to change the lives of others, impact my community, become a leader, and be changed in the process as well.

I have seen how my dad, who is a doctor, is respected within our community locally and even globally.  I admire the way that people call on him for help and how others respect him for the skill set that he has.  I want to one day be able to provide similar guidance and services for my community and patients.

In the past, serving my community is something that has always made me feel good. As a professional, I look forward to serving my community and being someone that people seek for advice and help.  As a professional I will have a specific set of skills that will allow me to distinguish myself and with these skills I know I will be able to serve my community on an even greater level than before.
My mission in dental school is to obtain the skill set I need to be a successful and competent practitioner, and graduate on time! I want to make an impact in the community and be a leader.

I want to use the dental skills I will obtain in this program and combine them with my anthropological background to promote oral health as a public health concern in marginalized communities in the United States and abroad.

Ethics is equally important as any aspect in being a competent professional. As healthcare providers, patients give a lot of trust in you to provide them with the care they need. It is important not to abuse this trust.
I want to be able to learn as much as I possibly can here. I want to provide the best possible care to my patients while earning an honest living. I want to be one of the best dentist in the world.

In order to become a professional, you must have a deep understanding in your specialty. This means you must exert all possible effort and gather all possible resources in order to achieve this knowledge. I want to achieve as much as possible in order to provide the best care. Professionalism includes maturity and the way you carry yourself.

So far, I have not gained much progress. I have done what it takes to get into dental school but most of my professional progress will be learned here.

To develop a sound knowledge of dentistry, incorporating the experiences, connections, and relationships gained throughout dental school to provide the best possible healthcare for my future patients.

Attending dental school not only provides an outstanding understanding of the science and beauty of the practice of dentistry but also the pleasure of building personal and professional relationships. These relationships are what allow dentistry to be a rewarding profession.  As a dental school student, I want to develop very strong interpersonal relationships with my colleagues as well as my professors. Over the four years, I want to be able to build a strong network of professionals who can rely on myself as a clinician and vice versa. As a student, I want to establish a growing passion for dentistry and develop an inspiration that will continue to make dentistry rewarding in the near future. Upon doing research and volunteering in the orthodontic field, I want to provide orthodontic care to patients in need whether in an office setting or through an outreach program. As a healthcare provider I believe communication is imperative, not only to the patient but with other professionals as well.

As a student at dental school, I want to establish professional and personal relationships within the dental field with both patients and other professionals. Acquiring the technical hands skills and practicing them with great proficiency will be another important aspect I would want to take out of my four years of school.

Over the next four years I want to first and foremost gain the clinical skills required to become the best possible practitioner. In addition I want to build strong relationships with my peers and future colleagues, and feel like a part of the NYUCD community. Also deepen my passion for dentistry by gaining the hands on experience of working with patients.

It is important to me to set high standards for myself-- I believe there are three main components to being a great dentist which I stated in my public mission statement--knowledge, artisanry, and empathy. I am looking to build upon these characteristics at NYU to become the best professional I can be. To do so I will be ambitious and goal set and will not let anxiety or stress get the best of me. I will not forget the primary reason I am here is to help people and will perform community outreach programs whenever possible. And lastly, but most importantly, to stay true to my values and who I am.
My mission: to improve the lives of others in my community through the knowledge, artisanry, and interpersonal skills/empathy reaped through education at NYU.

Our ethics course has brought up some very thought provoking situations. Most of the class agreed that in most ethical cases, they would not get involved. I too agree that getting involved is much harder than saying nothing at all. I do think that every situation is complex in its own way, and has so many factors involved. I know that once the pressure of achievement is weighing heavier on me, ethics will be much harder to maintain, but I hope that I will continue to preserve ethics in throughout my time in dental school and beyond.

My mission is to develop the knowledge and skills I will need to become a competent dentist through my experiences and hard work. I hope to develop productive habits under a high stress environment, as well as develop a strong passion for the dental profession. I plan to work with and learn about different populations and cultures, in order to broaden the type of care I will provide in the future.

I also feel that becoming a professional means having to prioritize my education about all else, because becoming a professional is a responsibility. Once you are a professional, people trust you with their health, and I hope to learn as much as I can so I do not let these people down.

Being a professional to me is presenting my self in a manner that patients will see me as trustworthy and knowledgable. Besides appearance, professionalism also means someone who values a field and dedicated their time to perfecting the skills of this field in order to give back to that field. So in dentistry, being a professional dentist to me is learning as much as you can in order to treat patients properly, contribute to advances in the field, and being active in continued education.

My mission is to develop the knowledge and skills I will need to become a competent dentist through my experiences and hard work. I hope to develop productive habits under a high stress environment, as well as develop a strong passion for the dental profession. I plan to work with and learn about different populations and cultures, in order to broaden the type of care I will provide in the future.

NYUCD expects a great deal from their students and I too aim to set high expectations for myself, not solely limited to academics. I hope to meet many interesting individuals whom I can share a close bond with and feel comfortable calling upon them in the future. I also look forward to joining the outreach programs to help out in all types of communities.

Like others working in the health care field, dentists must adhere to the standards of being a doctor on and off "the court." I believe that professionalism sets its roots in the early-phase training of doctors, in the classroom and amongst one's peers, long before a dentist or other health care practitioner can begin to practice in the real world. How one behaves during the beginning phases set precedent for how he/she will behave later in live, both mentally for the individual as well as in the eyes of those with whom he comes to work. Undoubtedly, the moment we become doctors and part of a bigger community, we must follow strict guidelines as to how to behave in society. Thus, when one dentist/doctor acts dishonestly or in bad taste, we as health care professionals all feel the repercussions on one's wrong doing. This is why set guidelines are in effect and accordingly, why those who regard  themselves as doctors should hold to those very standards.

My goal over these next four years, at NYUCD, is to gain the proper knowledge and hand skills to be able to care for my patients with professional competence. I appreciate the opportunity I have been given to fulfill my ambition of working within the dental field.

In addition to my education, involvement in campus activities such as membership in Sigma Phi Epsilon fraternity developed my ability to communicate confidently in groups and have input to the achievement of team goals. This was further amplified when I became President of Recruitment for the organization. During my term I would be in charge of all matters regarding attracting prospective members. I would hold numerous recruitment events on and off campus, screen interviewees, and create a recruitment plan to be used by my successor. While I would be primarily responsible for my duties in this position, I realized more positive results would be attained by creating a diverse recruitment team to collaborate with, and this proved true. My short stint as a Sales Associate before entering Graduate school would provide valuable experience in communicating with others and displaying a positive attitude. I hope that these experiences will aid in my tenure at NYUCD.

Upon completion of my Master of Science Degree I am thankful for the experience as a graduate student which allowed me to continue to develop as a student and as a person. I am confident in my abilities to contribute to the diverse learning environment of a Dental School and ultimately the profession of Dentistry.

Entering dental school has been an experience that differs from other educational endeavors because this is specific training for my career and lifetime occupation. This type of mentoring is unique and I want to become a better leader, dentist and human being through my studies at New York University College of Dentistry. There are some areas that I know need improvement in such as communication and objectivity which will allow me to become a better Dental professional. I look forward for my time management and focus to improve as well during this time.

I look to gain the experience and knowledge which will make me a confident dentist and achieve a passion that will allow me to build my interest in the profession on a day to day basis. I hope to set an example as a dental professional which has a positive impact on patients and the community.

I strive to master the technical skills of dentistry in order to provide utmost professional care to my patients, while establishing effective communication skills and maintaining positive rapport with my patients. I also strive to build and maintain strong connections with other medical professionals.

I strive to master the technical skills of dentistry in order to provide utmost professional care to my patients, while establishing effective communication skills and maintaining positive rapport with my patients. I also strive to build and maintain strong connections with other medical professionals. With the education and skills I acquire at NYUCD, I know I will be able to accomplish this.

All of the decisions I have made up to this point have steered me into a career that I will strive to succeed in. I am excited to grow my passion in dentistry and have a career that I can essentially support myself and my family in the future.

In having been a dental hygienist prior to entering dental school, I have a strong sense of what it feels like to impact a patient's life, whether it be by brightening his or her smile, or by being there just to listen to them. I am excited to take what I have learned and am ready to develop an even stronger sense of what professionalism entails.

It amazes me how much society values professionals and look at them with such respect. I want to learn great oral health practices that I can teach to people I know and don't know. As a dentist, after those rigorous four years coming ahead, I want to help those in need and cannot afford health care. I want to be a healing hard to those with oral health problems that have no dental insurance. I want to reach out to the community and address the social responsibility that we all have through helping as a dentist. To my peers and faculty members I would like to be an understanding and approachable individual who stays optimistic in times of adversity and perseverance. In addition, I want to join different clubs offered by NYUCD and be an active member of the community.

My goal is to become a proficient dentist who is prepared to enter the practicing world as a professional when I leave school. I will do my best to succeed in class while still maintaining time to relieve stress. I am excited to be part of the NYU Dental Class of 2017! In additional to gaining the technical skills and knowledge to become an excellent dentist, I hope to participate in extramural commitments to improve myself. Specifically, I intend to network with peers through interest clubs and gain a better understanding of the service-learning in dentistry via international outreach programs. I expect the next four years to be challenging -with lectures, labs and clinics- but I look forward to the experience and the many friends to be made along the way.

Over the next four years, it is my desire to immerse myself in learning the various principles and disciplines of dentistry and strive for excellence in learning and applying the same. Over the next four years, it is my desire to immerse myself in learning the various principles and disciplines of dentistry and strive for excellence in learning and applying the same. I hope to graduate not just a competent and a confident dentist, but also a facilitator in the process of achieving greater health standards in the community I hope to serve.

To become a competent professional dentist, I need to gain foundational knowledge and formative experience. The foundational knowledge will be obtained through my daily classes at school, particularly in my D1 and D2 years, as well as from primary literature found on PubMed and from informative product shows and conferences that I attend during my spare time. Formative experience will be obtained throughout dental school starting with basic simulation training in D1 and D2, followed by practical real-life training with patients in D3 and D4. Continual practice will improve my skills and will allow me to become competent as a dentist. Evaluation of my competency level will be determined by my professors and myself. While my professors may feel that I am competent at a particular skill, if I am not comfortable with performing the skill, then I am not competent. Striving to become a competent dentist takes hard work and dedication, and it is what I hope to achieve by the end of dental school in four years.

During my time at the New York University College of Dentistry, I aim to improve my academic knowledge and dexterous hand skills in dentistry to a level of excellence so that I have the confidence and ability to treat patients well. I also intend to develop my peer network through social interactions with my classmates and faculty, during which time I will also improve my communication skills. Being in New York City also provides me with the opportunity to live and function independently to prepare me for my future. Lastly, as NYUCD has a wide variety of opportunities available, I would like to join at least one club each year and partake in dental community service to help both the local and global society while furthering my skills.
Like my fellow classmates, I have a sincere interest in becoming a competent dentist. This will inspire me to keep trying my best and learn about my mistakes with an open mind.
I will strive to meet academic standards, learn to work better in a team, and develop networks with future colleagues while maintaining a balanced lifestyle.

As a community leader, I will abide by all the ethical and legal standards that are required for a dentist during my diagnosis, treatment planning, management of patient records, and handling in special circumstances. Not only as a health care provider, I will maintain ethics as a good citizen.

I will stay on top of every course material in order to strive through rigorous dental curriculum with efficient time-management skills and diligence. I will also pay attention to balance the educational duty with social relationship with my colleagues.

I do not feel I am competent enough to be called professional at this moment in many aspects. Not only didactic knowledge and clinical skills of a dentist, I will be competent to be professional in time-management, communication, respect, appearance, and responsibility for the community.

I do have many aspects lacking to be competent for a professional at this moment. However, I am ready to absorb education, manners, communication skills along with ethics and respect for others in order to be a professional. My ability of self-abasement and accepting peer evaluation will teach me my strengths and weaknesses in order to improve myself.
As the year goes, I will self-assess myself in order to judge my strengths and weaknesses that I need to improve.

I want to be a student with thorough scientific knowledge and clinical hand skills, who can adapt criticism as a means to improve oneself and who can effectively and emotionally communicate with patients and colleagues. I will be the community leader who feels genuine empathy and responsibility for community and provides outstanding dental care to people in needs.

I think having the right knowledge and truthful to people you meet or treat is important. My understanding is that it is important to have an open minded of things, especially when it comes to dealing with people because everyone has a different background. I think this is important when it comes to professions like dentistry where you require direct communication with patients.

I hope to achieve a better knowledge of being a professional as well as education. Through various experiences at school, both education and communication with different people, I hope to develop better skills to become a better professional, or a dentist. I hope to gain a lot of experience through volunteer work so that I have more knowledge of treating different people and have a better idea about the profession I am currently studying as well as about my community.

Through my experiences at school, I hope to have a broader understanding about being a professional and how to communicate with various people. One of my weaknesses is confidently communicating with people, but I hope to develop better skills, as I will be dealing with more and more people, I hope to overcome this.

I think being a professional is not only having the necessary education, but having an open minded attitude and being able to understand and deal with various situations in a mature manner. Through my experience at school and interaction with people from different backgrounds, I hope to develop a broader mind set about people and situations, which I believe is a necessary part of being a professional.

By learning about dentistry, I believe I will develop the right skills to become a professional. Obtaining knowledge, interaction with diverse people and patients, and volunteering in my community, will help build a better foundation to be a professional, and to treat and care for people.

Through the four years of dental school, I hope to achieve my goal of being a more mature, professional individual who can become a helpful resource to the community. I hope to gain not just the facts and techniques of dentistry but about the relationships and communication skills between professionals, peers and patients. Also to learn to not just treat patients, but to care for them by getting more involved in my community and being more active in dental field.

Based on what we learned throughout the orientation and the first few classes on 'Professionalism and Ethics,' a dentist requires not only the skills and knowledge as a technician and a practitioner, but also a sense of conscience and ethical background to refrain from making mistakes or maltreating patients.

The primary reason why I chose dentistry as my lifetime career is because I am always fond of those who laugh unaffectedly and have big smiles on their faces at most times. And my goal here is to give them even better smiles, smiles that are not just unaffected and big, but beautiful aesthetically. For such reason, I am most interested in cosmetic dentistry, more specifically in orthodontics and orthognathia, if my grades turn out to be on that level. Also, I'd really want to continue on with my experience in chorals (singing), and probably further develop it as my second career if time permitting.

Of course, making a living by doing what you learned in school or institutions is one big part of being a professional, but I believe meeting the expectations of the people who ask for our services is the more important part of being the "real" professional career-wise. I hope I can satisfy what my future patients expect of me, and I will endeavor to make it possible.

Becoming a professional in every career requires a deep understanding of knowledge and skills related to the field because customers (patients in our case) expect a certain amount of professionalism from the workers they consult.
Hope to see this updated in the near future! No words to say for now, but I will make records as years run on.

I will become a dentist who really cares about patients' concerns, open-minded to criticisms from colleagues and other professionals. I will never hesitate to take in people's ideas and make improvements based on the constructive criticisms given upon me. Outside my school life, I will retain my private life, managing time and stress effectively so that my own concerns will not affect my practice in the clinics.

I believe being ethical in one's work is to be responsible for the safety and total well being of your patients. I think that in the next four years I will learn many of these methods in theoretical and clinical settings. However I also believe that to be an ethical practitioner is an on going learning process, that will be carried out throughout my practice.

I am looking forward to developing methods of improving the field of dentistry through advancements in technology. Also I am looking for ways that I can be a community advocate for oral health in my surrounding community.

To be a professional is to be responsible and held accountable for your actions. As I am trusted with the well being of others, I must hold my actions to a higher standard, that will always allow the highest care for my community.

I believe that becoming a professional is to hold true a set of principals that the public has trusted you with. I believe that it is important not only be competent in such responsibilities, but also an advocate for further advancing one's field of work. I look forward in learning such responsibilities and method for improving my field within the next four years.

Being a professional is an ongoing learning process. As I go on throughout my career, I will learn how to deal with every day responsibilities better, and therefore be a better advocate of oral health within my community.

My goal in the next four years is develop the theoretical, clinical and ethical skills that I need to be an advocate for oral health. I look forward to being a committed member of community outreach programs and organizations that provide such advocacy. Also, I plan to discover new clinical and technological developments in the field of dentistry.
I hope to get involved in the Survivors of Torture Program. I hope to look into a specialty.

My intentions as a future dentist are to promote happiness, health and overall wellness in the lives of individuals as well as the greater community. I desire to become a confident and competent professional by growing alongside my colleagues and self-improving along the way. I will seek a balanced lifestyle and aspire to be the best I can be.  I also intend to have an active role in the NYU community specifically in the realm of environmental conservation and sustainability.

There are so many things which impacted my decision to be a dentist, but now that I'm here I realize that I want to use my career to help my family. Being a professional starts from day one and I'm going to strive to be more professional every day.

To leave a legacy at NYU that will improve the community I am part of through outreach, participation and hard work. Abiding by a code of ethics is an integral part of being a competent professional. It is our job to maintain the public's trust in dentists, while providing our patients with outstanding healthcare, and we can only do this if we are ethical in all facets of our practice.

The more ethics courses I go to (this applies to other courses as well, but to a lesser degree), the more I realize that I, as a future doctor, have a very serious social contract with society.  As someone pointed out, patients are most likely not going to care about how much work their crown took to make, or how much studying and practice I had to do in order to be capable of doing what I am doing. Patients will come in with the expectation that in that moment and in that place I will do my job well. Nothing previous matters.
The reason I am writing this is because that will be my responsibility as a professional. I will have to make social, personal, and financial sacrifices because that is what becoming a professional entails. There is no use in complaining; instead, I should accept it and respect it.

Ethics are as important to one's self as they are to others. One must be truthful to one's self before dealing with others. Aside from this, the point of ethics is to establish a trust between the consumer and the professional. The actions of a professional often reflect upon the profession as a whole (albeit not in all instances). Thus it is vital to engage in ethical practices and behavior, and this starts with one's personal life. If one is an ethical person in general, that will translate well in their profession.

I know how hard it was to get to this point. Many things had to go right, and thankfully, they did. At 26 years old, the opportunity that I have now is a once-in-a-lifetime chance, and I intend to fully take advantage of it.
